{Game 3 W.Steinitz-F.Deacon 1st matchgame, London 1863 King’s Gambit
Following the Dubois match, Steinitz soon further enhanced his London
reputation by comfortably despatching the young English hopeful, Joseph Henry
Blackburne (1841-1924), in another match that ended, rather one-sidedly, +7 -1
=2. Steinitz then just as impressively defeated the Anglo- Belgian player,
Frederic Deacon (1829-1875), by another large match score, +5 -1 =1. At this
stage in his career, the Kieseritzky Gambit was one of his Steinitz’s
favourite openings and there is plenty of evidence to suggest that he worked
harder off the board on its complicated lines and more profoundly grasped the
opening’s strategic essence than most of his peers. Steinitz combines subtle
strategic motifs and hard-hitting tactics in a particularly satisfactory way
in this game.} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ne5 Nf6 6. Bc4 d5 7.
exd5 Bd6 8. d4 Nh5 9. Nc3 Qe7 10. Bb5+ c6 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Nd5 Qe6 13. Nc7+
Bxc7 14. Bc4 Qe7 15. Bxf7+ Kf8 16. Bxh5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Qe2 Qxh5 19.
Bxf4 Bf5 20. O-O Nd7 21. Bh6+ Kf7 22. Rxf5+ Qxf5 23. Rf1 Qxf1+ 24. Qxf1+ Kg6
25. Bg5 h6 26. Qd3+ Kh5 27. Be7 {Bachmann: Schachmeister Steinitz Bd. 1, p. 59}
1-0

