{Game 4 A.Anderssen-W.Steinitz 3rd matchgame, London 1866 Evans Gambit
Steinitz’s extraordinary 8-6 match win against Anderssen, in which every
game was decisive, came as a surprise to almost everyone other perhaps than
Steinitz himself. Steinitz certainly considered that he was strong enough to
defeat the old maestro, but was in no doubt that he faced a formidable
challenge to do so. Aged 48, Anderssen was still widely held to be Europe’s
foremost player, but his years were beginning to count against him. Steinitz
was his most dangerous opponent – highly innovative, thoroughly prepared and
doggedly-resilient. Steinitz’s success rested mainly on a judicious choice
of ambitious but solid openings, which included a fine 3/4 score, with a novel
strategic reinterpretation of the long neglected Salvio Gambit, and a stubborn
3/6 against Anderssen’s greatly feared Evans Gambit.} 1. e4 {1)Deutsche
Schachzeitung 1866, p. 277; 2)The Chess World 1866/67, p. 174 3)Von Gottschall:
Adolf Anderssen.S.301-302.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. d4
exd4 7. O-O d3 8. Qxd3 ({Die bessere Fortsezung} 8. Ng5 {war von Andersen
selbst vor der Partie empfohlen worden.} Nh6 9. Nxf7 Nxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11.
Qh5+ g6 12. Qxc5 d6 13. Qd5+ Be6 14. Qxd3 {Von Gottschall, S.301:„Es ist
daher unbegreiflich, daß er diese von ihm selbst empfohlene Fortsetzung in
einer so wichtigen Partie nicht wählte“}) 8... d6 9. Bg5 Nge7 10. Nbd2 h6
11. Bh4 O-O 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. h3 Be6 {Black has a comfortable game and now
prepares to develop his queen on d7 and centralize his rooks, possibly
followed by an eventual, simplifying exchange of light-squared bishops.} 14.
Rad1 Qd7 15. Bd5 Ng6 16. Bg3 Rae8 17. c4 Bxd5 18. exd5 Nce5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20.
Qc3 Ng6 21. c5 dxc5 22. Nxc5 Qf5 23. Nxb7 Re2 24. d6 cxd6 25. Nxd6 Qe6 26. a4
Bd8 27. Qc5 f5 28. Qxa7 f4 29. Bh2 Nh4 30. Qb7 Qg6 31. Rd4 Bb6 32. Rdd1 Re6 33.
a5 Bc5 34. a6 Re7 35. Qd5+ Kh8 36. a7 Bxa7 37. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 38. Rxe1 Kh7 39. Qe4
Rf6 40. Nb5 Re6 41. Qxg6+ Rxg6 42. Nxa7 Rxg2+ 43. Kh1 Rxh2+ 44. Kxh2 Nf3+ 45.
Kg2 Nxe1+ 46. Kf1 Nd3 47. Nc6 Kg6 48. Ke2 Nc5 49. Kf3 Ne6 50. Ne5+ Kf5 51. Nd3
g6 52. Ne1 Nd4+ 53. Kg2 Ke4 54. Kf1 f3 55. Kg1 g5 56. Kh2 h5 57. Kg3 Nf5+ 58.
Kh2 g4 59. hxg4 hxg4 60. Kg1 Kd4 61. Nc2+ Kd3 62. Na3 g3 63. Nb5 g2 0-1

