{Game 5 W.Steinitz-H.Bird 13th matchgame, London 1866 French Defence Henry
Bird (1830-1908), challenged Steinitz to a match that was played shortly after
the Anderssen encounter. An accountant, who poured huge amounts of his spare
time into the game, Bird was ebullient, self-confident and tactically alert,
but had an unorthodox, strategically much shakier playing style than Steinitz
and was also occasionally prone to overestimating his chances in rash bids to
steamroller opponents. Bird rated his chances highly, of course, but no one
else did. Bird had to break off the match, due to pressing business
commitments, when trailing -6 +5 =5, with one game unfinished (but winning for
Steinitz). Steinitz, declared the winner, might have scored better. Bird
spluttered about the outcome for years, but he couldn’t ever match his
opponent’s depth of understanding and secure all-round playing skills.} 1. e4
e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nc6 5. Nf3 f5 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Bb4
8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Ne5 Na5 11. Bb3 b6 12. Re1 Nxb3 13. axb3 Bb7 14.
Nd3 Ne4 15. Bb2 Qh4 16. f3 Ng5 17. Qe2 Rf6 18. Qf2 Rg6 19. Qxh4 Nxf3+ 20. Kf2
Nxh4 21. Nf4 Nxg2 22. Nxg6 Nxe1 23. Rxe1 hxg6 24. Rxe6 Kf7 25. Re2 Be4 26. Bc1
Rh8 27. Kg3 Ke6 28. c4 c6 29. h4 a5 30. Bf4 Kd7 31. c3 Ra8 32. Be5 a4 33. bxa4
Bd3 34. Re3 Bxc4 35. Bxg7 Rxa4 36. Kf4 Ra1 37. Bh6 Rg1 38. Bg5 Rg4+ 39. Ke5 Bd5
40. Re1 Re4+ 41. Rxe4 Bxe4 42. Kf6 f4 43. Bxf4 {The Chess World 1866/67, p. 246
}) 4. Bg5 Be7 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bd3 Bg4 7. f3 Be6 8. Nge2 c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qd2
Nbd7 11. Bb5 Be7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Bxd7 Nxd7 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nf4 Nb6 16. Rhe1
Rfd8 17. Qe3 Nc4 18. Nfxd5 Qf8 19. Qf4 Bxd5 20. Nxd5 Rxd5 21. Rxd5 Qb4 22. Re4
Qxb2+ 23. Kd1 Qb1+ 24. Ke2 Qxc2+ 25. Ke1 b5 26. Rd7 Rf8 27. Rxf7 Qb1+ 28. Kf2
Qxa2+ 29. Kg3 Qa3 30. Rxf8+ Qxf8 31. Qg5 Qd6+ 32. Kh3 Qd7+ 33. g4 h6 34. Qg6
Nd6 35. Rd4 Qb7 36. Qxd6 Qxf3+ 37. Qg3 Qf6 38. Qd3 a5 39. Rd8+ Kf7 40. Qd5+ {
The Chess World 1866/67, p. 300 1-0 (40) Steinitz,W-Bird,H London 1866   Tips
and Endpoints Only five main games so far, but note that one of the main
threads that runs through all of them is the fundamental importance of good
tactics to success in chess. Small mistakes, as well as the occasional clear
error, crop up frequently in chess, even at the very top. In all of these
games, Steinitz got more of the tactics right and reduced his own error count
much more impressively than his opponents, especially at critical points. If
you want to improve at chess – always work hard on your tactics and
calculation skills. Steinitz’s overall evaluations and game-plans also
impress. Good plans depend on correct evaluations of a wide range of material,
structural and other more dynamic factors, such as good development, space and
time advantages. Note, however, that correctness in chess is rarely absolute,
which points both to the existence of valid, yet competing interpretations and
to a constant need to reconsider and make any essential adjustments. Cultivate
an alert, open-minded and wholly flexible approach to the subtly demanding,
but always important evaluative and planning arts – and do keep planning!
Steinitz’s command of the opening also stands out, perhaps as much for its
psychological as well as its purely technical impact. Good opening play,
especially when based on innovative, well-researched, organically coherent
game-plans (including their typical middlegame transitions), rather than
narrow variations, tends to make life especially difficult for opponents, both
in their minds and objectively. Grapple with the fundamental strategic
purposes of the opening, not just the latest variations or largely illusory
‘blockbuster’ moves – aiming primarily to understand and generate
generally playable game-plans, including their links to the middlegame.} 1-0

