{Chapter Two Achieving Supremacy (1867-1876) Steinitz may have defeated Adolf
Anderssen in their 1866 match, but in the eyes of many he hadn’t yet clearly
demonstrated his superiority over the old master. Many considered that the
match might easily have gone either way. Steinitz had only forged ahead by
winning the last two games of the match and the two-point margin was itself
quite narrow over only 14 games. Of even greater significance was Steinitz’s
relatively inferior record in international tournaments. Having taken first
place at London 1851, the first great international tournament ever held, and
at London 1862, Anderssen had a claim to fame that was hard to match. Steinitz
finished sixth at London 1862 and was yet to win any great international
tournament. Others, too, of Steinitz’s own generation, including Kolisch and
Louis Paulsen, had shown that they might eventually have the full measure of
the German champion. In the absence of any formal process to decide a ‘world
champion’, and all but occasional opportunities to play in wellorganized
national and international tournaments (though these became more frequent
during the 1860s), it was, however, near-impossible to decide between the
competing reputational claims of perhaps four or five players to be considered
the de facto champion, a state of affairs that certainly continued into the
early 1870s. In the year after his match with Anderssen, Steinitz obtained two
opportunities to promote his tournament reputation, at Dundee and Paris. At
Dundee, however, despite a fine score (7/9), he could only secure second place,
a half-point behind another exceptionally gifted young player, Gustav Neumann,
one of Anderssen’s chess students. At the stronger Paris event, Steinitz
placed only third, behind the winner, Kolisch, and the rising Polish star,
Szymon Winawer, although he did manage to outdistance fourth-placed Neumann.
Throughout the late-1860s, while unbeaten in one-to-one match play, Steinitz
still had a point to prove in tournament chess. He had to wait three years for
his next big tournament chance, at Baden-Baden 1870. During those years,
Steinitz’s chess life, with its predominant mix of stakes chess, lessons,
exhibitions and occasionally more serious tournament or match play, continued
much as it had done before his match with Anderssen. At a personal level,
Steinitz now had a wife, Caroline (b.1847), with whom he lived in apparently
secure, if economically modest circumstances in a working-class area of East
London, and became more rooted. While Landsberger believes that the couple may
not have formally married, they certainly lived together as man and wife and
remained together as a family with their daughter, Flora, who was born towards
the very end the match with Anderssen. Baden-Baden 1870 was an outstanding
event that brought together an even stronger field than had competed at Paris.
Once again, Steinitz, who finished in second place, was an unlucky bridesmaid.
While he comfortably outclassed such leading lights as Blackburne, Neumann,
Louis Paulsen and Winawer, he had to concede first place to the rejuvenated
and evergreen Anderssen, who outdistanced him by a half-point and against whom
he lost both of their individual games. By Steinitz’s own later admission,
his Baden-Baden performance had been highly disappointing and often quite
erratic. The experience, however, convinced him to work much harder and embark
on a fundamental overhaul of his playing style. Whatever Steinitz did worked
wonders. In 1872, he won his first international tournament in London and
trounced the young Johannes Zukertort, +7 -1 =4, in match play. At Vienna 1873,
Steinitz then won one of the greatest tournaments of the age, scoring an
astonishing, +20 -2 =5, and defeating Blackburne, 2-0, in a tie-break. That
Steinitz and Blackburne tied, however, was more a quirk of the unusual
tournament regulations than a reflection of merit. The main event was decided
on a mini-match basis (each player met all the others in two-, or at most
3-game encounters). While Steinitz and Blackburne tied 10/11 (in mini-matches),
Blackburne, scoring +20 -9 =3, had laboured much harder than Steinitz to do
that. Steinitz’s magnificent result at Vienna 1873 marked a significant
breakthrough and his reputation soared. Writing in July 1874, in his recently
commissioned column in The Field , Steinitz at last felt bold enough to
suggest, in reply to a reader’s query about the world’s ‘best’ player,
that “pro tem ... Steinitz, who has not yet lost any set match on even terms,
and who has come out victorious in the last two international tournaments,
London 1872 and Vienna 1873 could claim the title of champion”. This quite
balanced view of Steinitz’s relative primacy was no doubt widely accepted,
subject to his modest rider that nevertheless “probably little difference
exists between several first-class players”. Steinitz’s change in
tournament fortune was matched by positive changes in his playing style. At
Vienna 1873, Steinitz notably extended his range of openings, building on a
successful adoption of 1 d4 in his two final white games in the Zukertort
match, to include a series of English and Queen’s Pawn openings. This marked
a move away from his early preference for the old open games and gambits
towards the more strategicallybased, closed openings, with their greater
emphasis on positional understanding, good planning and the manoeuvring arts
than direct tactics and towards the style to which he shifted almost
exclusively in his more mature years. Steinitz never completely gave up on one
or two of the old open games and even gambits, especially those that had more
interesting and underinvestigated strategic roots and provided ample scope for
his genius for opening innovation, such as the Kieseritzky and Salvio Gambits
and his own bamboozling Steinitz Gambit. Gradually, however, more Spanish
Games and Queen’s Gambits crept into Steinitz’s repertoire. He became an
increasingly all-round and even more exceptionally inventive player, whose
profound chess understanding, allied to his relish for surprise and experiment,
must have made him despairingly difficult to prepare against. During these
years, Steinitz’s column in The Field , which he conducted from 1873-1882,
rapidly became an international exemplar for a new level of deeply analytic,
incisive and highly objective game annotations. As he gradually became the
reputational world ‘champion’ by ever-wider acclaim, Steinitz’s stock as
a chess writer also soared. Chess players around the globe followed his
detailed commentaries on the top events and best games played in them avidly,
including the two great games played by correspondence between the London and
Vienna chess clubs (1873- 1874), and all seven games played in the
Steinitz-Blackburne match (London 1876). Steinitz’s seven point winning
margin against Blackburne, without conceding either a draw or a loss, was, of
course, remarkable. Adding these seven straight wins to his finishing run of
sixteen wins, at Vienna 1873, meant that Steinitz had won twenty-three
successive games at the very highest level. Few doubted Steinitz’s claim to
be considered the de facto champion in 1876 – pro tem perhaps, yet supreme!} 
*

