{Game 7 L.Paulsen-W.Steinitz Baden-Baden 1870 Three Knights Opening Louis
Paulsen (1833-91), a great amateur in the same mould as Anderssen, worked
quietly on the family farm for most of his life, while spending his spare time
studying and playing chess. One of the world’s top players in the 1860s and
70s, Paulsen was known for his many original opening insights and unusual
defensive tenacity, which, as has already been noted, made a profound early
impact on Steinitz’s own chess ideas and development. Private and reserved
in his personal life, Paulsen fizzed and bubbled on a chessboard. Once he had
absorbed Paulsen’s ‘lessons’ in the art of defence and positional play,
however, Steinitz, the all-round professional and even greater thinker,
generally had Paulsen’s measure in most of their tournament games.} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Bc4 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Bg5 Qd7 7. a3 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3
Nge7 10. h4 g4 11. Nd2 h5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Ne7 14. Bb3 f5 15. exf5 Nxf5
16. Nf1 c6 17. c3 Qc7 18. Qe2 Qb6 19. Ba2 Bd7 20. O-O-O O-O-O 21. f3 Nxg3 22.
Nxg3 d5 23. Kb1 Bf8 24. Ka1 Bd6 25. Nf1 Rdf8 26. Nd2 Rh6 27. c4 Be6 28. Nb3
gxf3 29. gxf3 Bc7 30. Nd2 Rhf6 31. Rc1 Kb8 32. cxd5 cxd5 33. Rhg1 Bd6 34. Rg5
Bf7 35. Nb1 Qd4 36. Nc3 a6 37. Rg7 Be6 {AJ Gillam: Baden Baden 1870, p. 41} 0-1

