{Game 8 W.Steinitz-J.Zukertort London 1872 Steinitz Gambit In his Modern Chess
Instructor , Steinitz wrote that “it is especially as regards the power of
the king that the modern school deviates from the [ ... ] old [ ... ] masters,
and we consider that the king must be treated as a strong piece both for the
attack and defence.” He added that “several [ ... ] openings have been
developed in which the king [ ... ] is brought into [early] action [ ... ] and
after withstanding a seemingly vehement attack, obtains perfect security with
the superior position, generally for the ending [ ... ] having gained some 
[material] advantage, but sometimes also in the middlegame.” This statement
of near lifelong Steinitzian faith, influenced in Steinitz’s earliest days
by the ideas of Hamppe (see Game 1), underpinned the birth of Steinitz’s own,
extraordinary Steinitz Gambit.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 exf4 4. d4 Qh4+ 5.
Ke2 d5 6. exd5 Bg4+ 7. Nf3 O-O-O 8. dxc6 Bc5 9. cxb7+ Kb8 10. Nb5 Nf6 11. Kd3
