{Game 9: J.Zukertort-W.Steinitz 5th matchgame, London 1872 Ruy Lopez Zukertort
developed his skills (not unlike Gustav Neumann), by playing numerous,
seriously contested ‘off-hand’ games, as well as a smaller number of more
formal tournament and match games, against his early mentor, Adolf Anderssen,
from the early 1860s to around 1872, when Zukertort decided on a permanent
move from Berlin to London. Having just defeated Anderssen, +5 -2, in their
second match, at Berlin 1871 (though this wasn’t a formal stakes contest),
Zukertort came with a glowing reputation. Although this was slightly dented by
his third place finish, behind Steinitz and Blackburne, at London 1872,
Zukertort nevertheless obtained sufficient backing to challenge Steinitz to a
match shortly afterwards. Steinitz, who won, +7 -1 =4, completely outplayed
him. In this game, he ensnares his opponent in a gradually enveloping
dark-square embrace that proves crushing.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4
Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. h3 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be3 c5 10. Qd2 h6 11. Rb1 Ng8
12. Nh2 Ne7 13. f4 exf4 14. Bxf4 g5 15. Be3 f5 16. O-O f4 17. Bf2 Nc6 18. Nd5
O-O 19. b4 cxb4 20. Nxb4 Nxb4 21. Rxb4 Be6 22. Bd4 Bxd4+ 23. Rxd4 c5 24. Ra4
Qb6 25. c4 a5 26. Ra3 a4 27. Rc3 Rfb8 28. Rc2 Qc7 29. Rb2 a3 30. Rbb1 Qg7 31.
Rxb8+ Rxb8 32. Qa5 Qd4+ 33. Kh1 Qxd3 34. Qc7 Rb1 35. Qd8+ Kf7 {Deutsche
Schachzeitung 1872, p. 321} 0-1

