228,228,228,304,401,401,401,490,519,674,697]} {Game 11 London Chess Club -
Vienna Schachgesellschaft Correspondence 1873/74 English Opening In his
International Chess Magazine (January 1890), Steinitz wrote that “the
systematic analytical development of modern ideas dates from the match between
London and Vienna”. Aided by William Potter, his main partner in the London
team, Steinitz devoted countless hours of analysis to these two prestigious
correspondence games, which the partners ably summed up in many hundreds of
words and high quality variations, in their exhaustive game annotations,
presented in The Field . Steinitz’s use of the words ‘systematic’ and
‘analytical’ reflect his new-found (1870s) zeal for the application of the
most rigorous scientific standards to probe the game’s truths, which ruled
out all appeal to general rules or unsubstantiated principles: “the
published analysis”, he wrote in The Field , “did not represent a tithe of
the variations [ ... ] gone through by the leaders of [this] contest”.} 1. c4
e5 2. Nc3 Bb4 3. Nd5 Be7 4. d4 exd4 5. Bf4 c6 6. Nxe7 Nxe7 7. Qxd4 O-O 8. e4 (
