{[%mdl 18528][%evp 0,67,19,16,33,47,24,-1,8,-4,0,0,1,-19,-9,-31,-13,-64,-4,-38,
-25,-30,-2,-26,-8,-29,30,22,27,26,71,58,46,5,36,17,43,2,16,-22,54,84,138,127,
134,115,129,94,109,74,75,92,148,36,242,326,403,444,418,431,505,629,606,616,623,
564,636,585,789,840] Game 12 W.Steinitz-J.Blackburne 1st matchgame, London
1876 Ruy Lopez According to Steinitz, in The Field , “it requires little
courage to step on the trodden paths of the gambits, where the way has been
paved by the ablest analysts and the strongest masters [ ... ] the
comparatively unknown irregular debuts [however] put the independent and
unassisted judgement of both players to a severe test”. Where others banked
on memory and book knowledge, Steinitz prized genuinely well-judged innovation.
His greatest native English rival, Joseph Henry Blackburne (1841-1924) must
have been unnerved by Steinitz’s spectacular creativity in this historic
game. Steinitz corrects Anderssen’s closed handling of the Spanish, 5 d3
opening (see Games 9 and 10), converting it into the popular modern and much
more viable system that we still hold in the highest regard today.    Esta
partida es una de las elegidas por Richard Reti, en su obra 'Los grandes
maestros del tablero', para mostrar el juego de Steinitz. Los comentarios
corresponden a ese libro.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6.
c3 {La formaciуn central favorita de Steinitz, para luego atacar en el flanco
rey sin temor a desуrdenes centrales.} Be7 7. h3 $5 {El plan de Steinitz
comprende avanzar en el flanco rey, mediante el oportuno g2g4.} O-O 8. Qe2 Ne8
9. g4 $5 {Impidiendo el contrajuego con ...f7f5 y preparando el pasaje de un
caballo hacia 'f5'.} b5 10. Bc2 Bb7 11. Nbd2 {Iniciando la maniobra para
llegar a 'f5' que, segъn indica Reti, aquн fue utilizada por vez primera.} Qd7
12. Nf1 Nd8 13. Ne3 Ne6 14. Nf5 g6 $6 {Un error estratйgico producto del
desconocimiento. Desaparecido el alfil de casillas oscuras, los puntos dйbiles
