{Game 13 W.Steinitz-J.Blackburne 5th matchgame, London 1876 Vienna Gambit
Blackburne never found it easy to play against Steinitz, especially at match
play (never his strongest suit), and his 0-7 drubbing at London 1876 saw him
reach an especially low point. He might have scored better, but Steinitz, who
scrambled back from the brink in several games, continually out-foxed him.
Whether defeating his opponent with a brilliant new game plan (see Game 12),
or simply benefiting from Blackburne’s occasional oversights, Steinitz could
apparently do little wrong against him. In this game, Steinitz’s battling
relentlessness carries the day, as he builds on a belief that his king in the
centre conveys an advantage that is, in fact, largely illusory. Steinitz
excelled at making the most out of almost any position. Blackburne, alas,
failed to grasp where his own chances lay in the most critical phases of this
game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 Bb4 5. fxe5 Nxe4 $6 6. dxe4 Qh4+ 7.
Ke2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 Bg4+ 9. Nf3 dxe4 10. Qd4 Bh5 11. Ke3 Bxf3 12. Bb5+ c6 13. gxf3
cxb5 14. Qxe4 Qh6+ 15. Kf2 Qc6 16. Qd4 Na6 17. Ba3 b4 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. Qxb4
Rc8 20. Rab1 b6 (20... Qxc3 21. Qxc3 Rxc3 22. Rxb7 Rxc2+ 23. Ke3 $11) 21. Rb3
Rd8 22. Re1 Rd5 23. Re4 Qh6 (23... Rc5) 24. h4 g5 $2 25. e6 fxe6 26. Qa4+ Ke7
27. Qxa7+ Rd7 28. Qxb6 Rc8 29. Qe3 Kf7 30. Rb5 Rcd8 31. Rxg5 Rd2+ 32. Kg3 R2d6
33. Rf4+ (33. Reg4) 33... Ke7 34. Qe5 Rd5 35. Rg7+ Ke8 36. Qf6 Qxf6 37. Rxf6
R8d6 38. Rxh7 Rc5 39. Rg6 Kf8 40. h5 Rdd5 41. Rxe6 Rxh5 42. Rxh5 Rxh5 43. a4
Rc5 44. Re3 Rc4 45. Kf2 Kf7 46. Ke2 Kf6 47. Kd3 Rxa4 48. c4 Ra1 49. c5 Ra4 50.
Re4 Ra1 51. Kc4 Ra4+ 52. Kd5 Ra3 53. c6 1-0

