{Chapter Three Attaining the Unchallenged Crown (1877-1886)  Having achieved
widespread acclaim as the world’s leading player in the years leading up to
and including his crushing 1876 match victory against Blackburne, Steinitz
then effectively withdrew from all serious match and tournament chess until
the second great Vienna tournament of 1882. During this period, he continued
to study the game and extended his serious chess writing, primarily in The
Field , whose increasingly expansive columns he conducted throughout this
period until 1882. Steinitz’s income from chess writing, allied to
exhibition and lecturing engagements and private instruction (he counted a
number of wealthy and well-placed establishment figures among his clients,
including Lord Randolph Churchill) must have significantly improved in these
years. At any rate, rather than battle for prizes and prestige in the next
great international tournament at Paris 1878, Steinitz covered the event,
solely as an on-site reporting journalist. While this may have made good
financial sense, Steinitz was nevertheless aware that by continuing to take
extended leave from top tournament and match play, he put his pre-eminent
reputation at risk without being able to defend it. Steinitz accordingly
announced in The Field that he “would acknowledge the [Paris] winner as his
perfect equal [and that if he] had not played [him] before, the winner will be
entitled to consider himself the superior”. Perhaps fortunately for
Steinitz’s reputation, the winner, Zukertort, still had a poor, head-to-head
record against him. As the 1870s wore on, Steinitz’s chess understanding and
writing grew in beneficial tandem and his reputation as a great teacher and
communicator, as well as the world’s leading chess player, also soared. In
1875, he had written in The Field , that “first-class players [ ... ] are
mostly guided [ ... ] by certain principles of judgement, which only want
expression to be made accessible to the generality of students”. Steinitz
had a genius for teasing out and clearly explaining such ‘principles of
judgement’, along with their subtle, ever-changing and often difficult
interaction with concrete variations that attracted students everywhere.
Gradually, however, Steinitz’s competitive urge began to reassert itself. As
the 1880s opened, it became clear that Zukertort’s star had dramatically
risen and that his claim to rival Steinitz’s supremacy could no longer be
denied. Following his outstanding victory at Paris 1878, Zukertort had
decisively defeated the French champion, Johannes Rosenthal, +7 =11 -1, at
London 1880 and Blackburne, +7 =5 -2, at London 1881. Most neutrals now
considered that Steinitz had a moral duty to return to the board to
demonstrate his supremacy or lose it to Zukertort by default. Steinitz
returned to the fray, taking up an invitation to play at the second great
Vienna tournament, in 1882. The year 1882 proved to be one of momentous change
for Steinitz. Despite almost six years’ absence from the top-class game,
Steinitz emphatically reasserted his de facto primacy at Vienna 1882, where he
finished in a well-merited share of first and second places with Winawer,
comfortably ahead of Zukertort (fourth/fifth equal). Shortly after the
tournament ended, however, and despite the pride in Steinitz’s performance
that most British chess players took in an essentially British achievement,
Steinitz suddenly resigned as the country’s foremost columnist in The Field .
Although Steinitz had become embroiled in an editorial dispute that seems to
have developed towards the end of play at Vienna, it remains unclear exactly
why this had to happen, who may have been most at fault and why there
couldn’t have been a reconciliation (as there had been before on one or two
occasions). Matters worsened (from a British perspective) when, later in 1882,
Steinitz travelled to America to embark on a long-planned tour of the New
World chess clubs, whose considerable financial and personal success
apparently persuaded him that his professional future best lay in the USA.
Steinitz organized his emigration in 1883, shortly after returning to London
from his American tour and after competing in the next big international
tournament at London 1883. Back on the chess board, Zukertort reinforced his
claim to superiority over Steinitz, by finished in clear first place, at
London 1883, where he scored an exceptional 22/26, which left second-placed
Steinitz fully three points behind him. Virtually all of the world’s top
players had played both in Vienna and London and there was no longer any real
doubt that these two great players really must slug it out in matchplay. After
two further gruelling years of difficult negotiation, in which neither side
ever willingly agreed that he was the ‘challenger’, the parties and their
backers finally signed the contract that committed them to play in a grand
contest in which the winner would be the first to score 10 wins (draws not
counting) in the first ever, formally organized match for the world
championship, at New York, St. Louis and New Orleans 1886. Purely personal
issues aside, transatlantic travel, venue and cost complications added
considerably to the negotiating challenges and delay in bringing the match
about. If only Steinitz and The Field had been able to resolve their
differences, what might have been? America’s gain was a considerable loss to
Great Britain. The match stakes, at $2,000 (or around £400) a side, were set
at an unusually high level that was greatly in excess of sums staked in
previous broadly comparable contests. In their 1876 match, for example,
Steinitz and Blackburne had played for stakes of £60 a side, in itself a not
inconsiderable sum and around the previous maximum at that time. It is, of
course, hard to assess the effective purchasing power of money for goods,
services, rents and property, in what was a very early industrial, far more
unequal and economically insecure Victorian age. Such stakes, however, must
have seemed quite eye-wateringly high to the mass of the USA and UK’s
population. In 1884, the Third Reform Act in Great Britain extended the
suffrage to include all males who either owned property worth at least £10 or
paid rent of £10 or more a year, which still excluded some 40% of the male
population. In his Chess History and Reminiscences , Henry Bird was
sufficiently moved by the size of the purse at stake to conclude that the
players’ equal contribution towards it was “a sum neither party could
afford to lose, even though they could tax their chess supporters for it”.
Bearing in mind that the winner would normally expect to refund his own
financial backers fully, usually with interest drawn from the loser’s stake,
the first world title match clearly did not offer quite the kind of $million 
(plus) purses, with reasonable financial guarantees in place for both players,
that we have since seen in the late 20th and early 21st centuries. The
unfortunate 1886 loser obtained only his (at least quite generous) expenses
and a share of the take at the gate. Both players therefore had to play for
the big prize with one eye on how they might continue to secure regular,
ongoing income from other sources. In Steinitz’s case, he added to his usual
chess activities a new, privately-owned, International Chess Magazine , which
ran from 1885- 1891. Remarkably, he even felt constrained to regularly edit
the magazine’s content (much of it his own), while he took on Zukertort.
Steinitz, who started the great match as very slight favourite, eventually
overwhelmed his opponent, after a poor start, in which he went three wins down
in the first five games. Although six years older than Zukertort, Steinitz 
(aged 49) proved to be the stronger match player, not just technically
superior, but also the more fearless fighter and fitter physically, eventually
running out clear winner, scoring 10-5 in wins (with 5 draws). Steinitz
regularly outplayed Zukertort in a match that featured mainly closed and
semi-closed games of a confusingly structural and manoeuvring nature that gave
his opponent little chance to demonstrate his undoubted talent for
combinational brilliancy. Steinitz showed a marked superiority in the opening,
which he played with greater variety, enterprise and ingenuity than Zukertort,
and whose transitions into typical middlegames he understood and played much
more profoundly. Towards the end of the match, Zukertort’s weaker nerves and
physical frailty began to tell even more than Steinitz’s incessant
onslaughts. Completely exhausted, his final loss in a Steinitz Gambit, which
Steinitz had studiously reserved for such a moment of obvious frailty (see
notes to Game 8) was calamitous. In Steinitz, however, Zukertort faced a
‘champion’, once again at the very top of his game, an unstoppable
juggernaut.}  *

