{[%evp 0,69,19,33,33,-14,37,2,-6,-57,-65,-80,-65,-67,-58,-69,-58,-46,-49,-31,
-32,-28,18,17,37,37,54,54,68,77,112,101,103,91,148,162,162,134,158,138,152,135,
135,133,189,148,198,119,511,511,533,533,400,384,400,365,465,278,278,259,341,
342,439,395,522,453,771,765,29993,29994,29997,29998]} {Game 14 M.Steinitz-M.
Weiss Vienna 1882 French Defence In My System , Aron Nimzowitsch wrote that
Steinitz was “deepest and greatest in his conception of the centre”. In
this game, which strikingly supports this view, Steinitz anticipates many
ideas about play in the centre and on the flanks that we would now judge to be
thoroughly ‘hypermodern’. Max Weiss (1857-1927), one of Europe’s top
players in the 1880s, is thrown into considerable confusion by his
opponent’s bewilderingly visionary strategy. Rather than occupy the centre
with pawns, Steinitz, rather less conventionally, for the times, rushes to
clear it, especially the e5- square, which he then almost manically
‘over-protects’ (à la Nimzowitsch), backed up by centralized rooks and
knights, and two powerfully fianchettoed (Richard Réti-like) bishops. Using
e5 as a critical ‘pivot’ (another Nimzowitsch term), Steinitz is then able
to focus overwhelming force and win on Black’s weaker flank (Black’s
battered kingside).} 1. e4 e6 2. e5 c5 3. f4 d5 4. exd6 Bxd6 5. g3 Bd7 6. Nf3
Bc6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 Nb6 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. b3 Be7 13.
Bb2 a5 14. a4 Nbd5 15. Nc4 Nb4 16. Rae1 Nfd5 17. Nfe5 Bf6 18. Qf2 Be8 19. g4
Rd8 20. g5 Be7 21. Ng4 Nc6 22. Qh4 Nd4 23. Be4 f5 24. gxf6 Nxf6 25. Nxf6+ Bxf6
26. Qxh7+ Kf7 27. Bg2 Rg8 28. Ne5+ Kf8 29. Rf2 b5 30. axb5 Bxb5 31. Bh3 Re8 32.
Re4 Bc6 33. Rxd4 cxd4 34. Ba3+ Be7 35. Bxe6 {Christiaan Bijl: Das II.
Internationale Schachmeisterturnier Wien 1882, p. 141} 1-0

