{[%evp 0,65,19,-16,-16,-42,31,29,41,-28,-2,-17,-9,-28,-28,-35,-16,-25,-29,-19,
24,-17,33,22,47,57,45,45,84,64,51,51,78,69,63,67,69,53,91,52,72,30,94,9,108,47,
238,231,232,223,268,265,288,347,355,355,533,517,597,588,650,643,652,643,662,
670,771,778]} {Game 15 W.Steinitz-G.Mackenzie Vienna 1882 Semi-Tarrasch
Defence Steinitz was one of the earliest players to develop effective
middlegame strategies to play against the isolated queen’s pawn (IQP). In
this game, Captain George H. Mackenzie (1837-1891), handles the IQP on the
whole quite dynamically, but overplays his attacking hand towards the end and
the defence triumphs. A professional player of Scottish extraction, who
emigrated to the USA to fight on the Union side in the American Civil War,
Mackenzie has the unique distinction of having won the U.S. Championship 
(twice, in 1871 and 1874) and the Scottish Championship (in 1888). Steinitz
held Mackenzie in high esteem both personally and as a player, and was ready
to concede that he might not unreasonably claim the title of world champion
‘tournament’ player after his greatest victory, at Frankfurt 1887.} 1. c4
e6 2. e3 c5 3. d4 d5 4. dxc5 {Steinitz wastes no time in encouraging his
opponent to accept an IQP. A modern player would have delayed this exchange
until Black had moved his dark-squared bishop (to save a tempo).} Bxc5 5. cxd5
exd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bd3 Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nbd2 Bb6 10. a3 {[#] Steinitz’s
knight (on d2) and his bishop (on d3) are slightly awkwardly placed (the
position is easier to play with these pieces on c3 and e2 respectively). The
text-move, however, attempts to demonstrate otherwise. Question: What is White
up to? Answer: White plans b4, followed by Nb3 and Bb2, after which (if all
goes to plan) White controls the long dark-square diagonal and can look
forward to occupying the open c-file and eventually planting a knight on d4,
firmly blockading the IQP. If White can then bring about simplifying piece
exchanges, it is likely that the IQP will become ever more truly a structural
target than a supportive source of dynamic attacking strength. Steinitz was
the first great player truly to grasp all that. But, of course, it’s not the
whole story. Aaron Nimzowitsch more aptly expressed the true character of the
classic IQP battle, insisting, in My System , that the IQP puzzlingly poses
the difficult question: “which predominates [its] static weakness or [ ... ]
dynamic strength”. After Steinitz’s many early successes against the IQP,
many players began to develop improved ways to build on the IQP’s upsides.
Be in no doubt that an IQP conveys dynamic strengths. The (black) IQP brings
significant pressure to bear on c4 and e4, while the ample space to its rear
affords considerable scope for active piece development. Moreover if the IQP
player should establish control on the open cand/ or half-open e-files, he
obtains a promising platform for attacking play in the centre and/or on the
flanks.} Ne7 {[#] Mackenzie’s choice certainly isn’t a bad one. Question:
What is Black’s plan and was there any better? Answer: In switching his
queen’s knight to the kingside (eventually g6), Mackenzie, who relished
space and direct attacking prospects, spies chances in the centre and on the
kingside. He judges that these are likely to (at least) balance any perceived
‘weakness’ of the IQP, which he intends, at least for now, to retain as a
firm central anchor on d5. Given Steinitz’s somewhat esoteric interpretation
of the opening – White effectively plays ‘Black’ – Black has other,
more direct options, including 10 ... d4, after which White can either
exchange pawns (seeking equality), or play the positionally murkier 11 e4, and
if 11 ... Bg4 12 h3 Bh5 13 Nc4, keeping the centre closed. Perhaps more
challenging is 10 ... Re8, a flexible developing move that keeps the ... d4
idea open, as in V.Osnos-I.Nei, USSR Championship,Tbilisi 1966, which was
quickly drawn, but looked rather better for Black, after 11 b4!? Bg4 12 b5!?
Ne5 13 Be2 d4! (now very well-timed) 14 exd4 Bxd4, with Black in the driving
seat.} 11. b4 Bf5 12. Nb3 Ne4 13. Bb2 Ng6 14. Nfd4 Bd7 15. Rc1 Rc8 {To repeat,
such complex, unbalanced IQP middlegames are, as Nimzowitsch correctly
maintained, generally difficult to assess and play for both sides. White may
argue that he has a slight pull, due to his grip on d4 and extra queenside
space, but Black has a firm grip on e4 and very active pieces} 16. Rxc8 Bxc8
17. Qc2 Qe7 18. Rc1 f5 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. bxc5 f4 21. Qb3 Nxf2 22. Bxg6 Qxe3 23.
Qxe3 fxe3 24. Bb1 Bg4 25. Re1 Nd1 26. Ba1 e2 27. Nxe2 Ne3 28. Ng3 Nc4 29. Re7
Rf7 30. Re8+ Rf8 31. Bxh7+ Kf7 32. Bg6+ Kg8 33. Re7 {Christiaan Bijl: Das II.
Internationale Schachmeisterturnier Wien 1882, p. 247} 1-0

