{[%evp 0,60,24,20,24,27,78,27,25,25,-35,-71,-71,-75,-71,-72,-79,-79,-67,-80,
-73,-63,-29,-32,-32,-21,-21,-26,9,3,3,-22,-25,-33,-21,-23,-23,-61,1,-4,-22,
-117,-254,-220,-220,-268,-202,-280,-391,-443,-211,-311,-390,-403,-245,-906,
-906,-1846,-1776,-29987,-29988,-29991,-29992]} {Game 16 J.Mason-W.Steinitz
London 1883 London System James Mason (1849-1905), an Irish-born player, whose
family had emigrated to the USA in 1861, won the U.S. Championship in 1876,
and began competing in Europe with distinction shortly thereafter. Never quite
able to persuade others that he was true ‘world champion’ challenger
material, he nevertheless gamely challenged Steinitz to a formal stakes match
just after Vienna 1882 had ended. Mason made much play of his third place and
two draws against Steinitz at Vienna, where Zukertort placed 4th/5th (with
MacKenzie), but he had little support. In any case, Steinitz and Zukertort
were already beginning to negotiate the terms, place and time of their own
match. At London 1883, Mason, now re-domiciled in Great Britain, finished in a
tie for 4th-6th places, well behind Zukertort (first) and Steinitz (second),
losing twice (without win) against both of them, and Mason’s challenge was
history.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 {Given the unassuming nature of White’s placid
second move, Black’s lively reply, perhaps a novelty (in 1883), is
completely justified. It tempts Mason into grabbing Black’s c-pawn.
White’s best reply is probably Gata Kamsky’s 3 e3, which retains a solid
centre and postpones the real battle to the middlegame} 3. dxc5 Nc6 4. Nf3 {
Steinitz now finds a way to build a strong pawn centre and soon regains his
pawn with at least equality. Question: Did White have anything better? Answer:
Mason seems to be at a loss for an active plan. White might at least have
tried to mix things up, by playing} (4. e4) 4... f6 5. e3 e5 6. Bg3 Bxc5 7. c3
Nge7 8. Nbd2 Bb6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nf5 {Although Black is better, White’s
game is solid and hard to break down. Such positions are best taken in easy
stages. Steinitz plays to obtain the bishop-pair and to provoke imbalance in
the centre, resulting in his obtaining a dynamic, advanced passed d-pawn in
the next few moves.} 11. e4 Nxg3 12. hxg3 d4 13. cxd4 exd4 {[#] Although
Black’s passed d-pawn is also isolated, it is very well supported by his
active pieces and constrains White’s forces in his half of the board. There
is, however, a possibility that White might get a bishop to d5, cut off the
defence of Black’s d-pawn from the rear and round it up with his knights and
queen. Steinitz would certainly have taken this into account. Exercise: Can
you spot how Steinitz planned to meet this? Answer: Steinitz would not just
have noticed this idea, but almost certainly also the clever gambit that he
plays on his 16th move, which he follows up with ... f5-f4, achieving a
powerful counterattack on the f-file. My guess is that Steinitz clearly
calculated every one of Black’s moves from now up to his 19th (including its
threat to exchange pawns on g3 and the important detail that White couldn’t
win Black’s d-pawn). The rest he would have left largely to judgement. How
did you fare?} 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Nb3 Bg4 16. Bd5 Ne5 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bd5 f5 19.
Nbd2 f4 20. Qa4 Nxf3+ 21. Nxf3 fxg3 22. fxg3 Qd6 23. Nh2 d3+ 24. Kh1 Be2 25.
Rxf8+ Rxf8 26. Bb3 Qxg3 27. Qd7 d2 28. Qxd2 Bc7 29. e5 Qxe5 30. Nf3 Rxf3 0-1

