Game 17 J.Zukertort-W.Steinitz World Championship (Game 1), New York 1886 Slav
Defence Steinitz reported in the International Chess Magazine , that the first
world championship match began in the Manhattan Chess Club, at 2pm on Monday
11th February 1886, with the moves played out on “the historical board and
men [ ... ] at which Paul Morphy won many of his brilliant victories”.
Well-prepared for the occasion, Steinitz was ready for one of his opponent’s
favourite openings, wrested an early initiative and fittingly won the point
with a finely judged combination of which Morphy himself would have approved.
Steinitz’s play, however, dipped in the next three games, which were marked
by “feeble manoeuvres [ ... ] and regular blunders on [Steinitz’s side]
and tactical surprises on [Zukertort’s]”. The New York part of the contest
eventually concluded with Zukertort in a surprise 4-1 lead, after which,
following a fortnight’s break, the match moved on to St. Louis.       Games
1 to 5 were played in New York City.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Bf5 $6 4. Nc3 (4.
cxd5 $1 cxd5 5. Qb3 Bc8 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Ne5 e6 8. Bb5 Qc7 9. Bd2 Bd6 10. f4 $16 {
Zukertort,J-Steinitz,W (05)/Wch/1886/}) 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7 6. a3 $6 {/\ c5, b4
Zukertort had shown a successful recent interest in advancing his c-pawn to c5
early in the opening and reinforcing his gain of space on the queenside, by
playing a3 and b4. This is still a potent idea for White (as White’s spatial
gain is not insignificant), although a modern player would no longer tend to
employ it at such an early stage.} (6. c5 b6 7. b4 a5 $17 {Steinitz}) 6... Bd6
$1 {Provocative. Very good chess psychology. Sehr gutes psychologisches Schach.
} (6... Ngf6 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Qb6 {! Euwe}) 7. c5 $6 (7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3
Ngf6 9. e4 $10 {Vukovic}) 7... Bc7 8. b4 {[#] Knowledgeable spectators would
have been aware that Zukertort had won two recent games on the back of such
advancing queenside pawns, against Rosenthal (London 1880), and Winawer 
(London 1883). Question: What are White’s plans and how should Black best
continue? Answer: White plans to complete his kingside development and then
further advance his a- and b-pawns. With pawns on a4, b5 and a5, the dangerous
pawn break a5-a6 looms (while a5, followed by b6 and plans based on opening
the b-file may also threaten). To counter such possibilities, Black must look
especially to the centre and/or the kingside for counterplay. If White makes
additional gains in either of these two sectors, Black is likely to be
squeezed horribly everywhere. Rosenthal chose an early ... a6 against
Zukertort, followed by ... 0-0 and ... Nf6-e4, but was outplayed by his
opponent, who eventually established an extended dark-square clamp (with pawns
on b6, c5, d4, e3, and f4), and eventually penetrated on the (subsequently)
opened a-file. Against Winawer, who embarked on a risky kingside attacking
idea (involving the moves ... Nfg4 and ... h5), Zukertort eventually
established an even stronger clamp (with pawns on b6, c5, d4, e5 and f4) and,
with the queenside blocked, won on the kingside. Steinitz concluded that Black
should rather seek to open play in the centre, wherever possible, by the early
advance of Black’s e-pawn. The main aim of his “change from the tactics of
Zukertort’s opponents”, not unlike ‘best’ play today, was to prepare
“the weakening of the adverse kingside”.} e5 9. Be2 (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nd4
$15) 9... Ngf6 10. Bb2 (10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nd4) 10... e4 $1 11. Nd2 h5 $1 {
[#] Still in his home preparation, Steinitz rejects the more conventional 11 ..
. 0-0 (which can’t be bad), in favour of a sharper alternative. Question:
What are Black’s plans? Answer: Steinitz sought “to compel the [ ... ]
push h3, for otherwise Black would enter with his knight at g4 and White could
not get rid of it excepting by an unfavourable exchange for the bishop, as h3
would be afterward of no use, on account of the reply ... Qh4”. He was also
alert to the possibility of developing his king’s rook, via h6, to join in
an eventual attack on the kingside. Due to Black’s well-entrenched pawn on
e4 and extra kingside space, Steinitz’s ambitious plan seems quite justified.
Black’s bishops already aim aggressively at White’s kingside and his
queen’s knight will also shortly shift to the kingside, via f8. White still
remains quite solid, however, and he retains his own extra queenside space.
Steinitz had surprised his opponent and may be very slightly better, but
Zukertort, too, has prospects.} 12. h3 $8 (12. b5 $6 Ng4 13. h3 Qh4 $1 $17 {
Steinitz}) 12... Nf8 13. a4 Ng6 14. b5 $6 (14. Nb3 $1 {Minckwitz} Nh4 15. g3
$15) (14. g3 {Schallopp} Qb8 $1 15. Nf1 Qc8 16. h4 Ng4 $17 {Vukovic}) 14... Nh4
15. g3 (15. Bf1 g5 $1 $17 {Steinitz}) 15... Ng2+ $1 16. Kf1 Nxe3+ 17. fxe3 Bxg3
18. Kg2 Bc7 {18...Rh6!? /\Rg6 Euwe} 19. Qg1 $2 (19. Qf1 Qd7 20. Kf2 Rh6 21. Ke1
