Game 19 W.Steinitz-J.Zukertort World Championship (Game 19), New Orleans 1886
Ruy Lopez The concluding New Orleans part of the match began with a draw in
the 10th matchgame, followed by two crushing Steinitz wins in the 11th and
12th games that gave Steinitz a lead for the first time in the match since the
first game. Steinitz’s greater variety of play and the sheer number of new
ideas with which he continually surprised his opponent in the opening were
beginning to wear Zukertort down. In this game, Steinitz varied his 7th move
in the same variation for the third time in the match, although this time he
described the move as “the ordinary continuation”. The line’s
‘ordinariness’, however, was as usual marked as much by Steinitz’s own
interpretation of its merits as by any moves previously played by others.
Zukertort initially stood up well to this test, but slumped tactically at his
19th to 21st and 25th moves.  Games 10 to 20 were played in New Orleans.} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Qe2
Be6 (8... O-O $2 9. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 10. Qxe7 Re8 11. Qxd8 $19) 9. d3 {Not d4,
since Black gets the chance to resolve his doubled pawns and would then have
the better game thanks to his bishop pair. WeiЯ spielt nicht d4, um Schwarz
nicht die Chance zu geben, seine Doppelbauern mit c5 aufzulцsen, da dieser
dann aufgrund des Lдuferpaares das bessere Spiel hдtte.} Nf5 (9... O-O 10. Nxf7
