{Game 20 W.Steinitz-J.Zukertort World Championship (Game 16), New Orleans 1886
Ruy Lopez Zukertort staged a spirited comeback in the 13th-15th matchgames to
reduce Steinitz’s lead, in wins, to 6-5. His recovery, however, was
shortlived. Steinitz struck back decisively in the 16th game, taking his lead
to 7-5, only three wins short of the ten game winning target. Zukertort’s
Berlin Defence once again let him down. Steinitz this time switched from 4 0-0
to a line based on 4 d3 that involved yet another novelty in a variation that
had first featured in the Zukertort-Rosenthal match, at London 1880. Black
should equalize, but, as so often with Steinitz’s innovations, the line
contains many fine points, not all of which Zukertort fully appreciated. By
now, Zukertort must have been sorely regretting the lack of a reliable
second-string defence against 1 e4 in his match repertoire.   Games 10 to 20
were played in New Orleans.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 {Anderssen's
