43,127,113,86,107,118,117,176,135,135,262,297,276,29993,29994] Game 21 W.
Steinitz-J.Zukertort World Championship (Game 18), New Orleans 1886 Ruy Lopez
Steinitz’s win in the 18th matchgame put him 8-5 ahead in wins and appears
to have effectively broken Zukertort’s resistance. More a bruising,
hand-to-hand struggle in the middlegame than a game without flaws, Zukertort
started brightly enough, but squandered many more chances than Steinitz. In a
repeat of the opening in the 16th matchgame (see Game 20), Steinitz was the
first to vary (on his 13th move). In the obscure play that resulted, Steinitz
successfully stuck to his innovative game-plan while a below par Zukertort
floundered. Steinitz’s win in this game came on top of a highly fortunate
draw in the 17th matchgame. He duly despatched an increasingly dispirited and
exhausted opponent in the 19th and 20th games to take the first ever, formally
‘recognised’ world title.   Games 10 to 20 were played in New Orleans.} 1.
