[Black "CHAPTER FOUR"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[EventType "tourn"]

{Chapter Four Remaing at the Pinnacle (1887-1892) Steinitz, who reached his
fiftieth birthday shortly after winning the world title in 1886, was aware
that increasing age might be one of his fiercest challengers in the next few
years. Thankfully his health and playing strength held up remarkably well, at
least into the early 1890s. In this period, Steinitz twice defeated Mikhail
Chigorin (1850-1908) and Isidor Gunsberg (1854-1930) once, in three world
championship matches. In addition to publishing his monthly International
Chess Magazine (1885-1891), he also completed Volume 1 of his Modern Chess
Instructor (1889) and extensive game annotations for the commemorative book of
the marathon, 38-round 6th American Chess Congress, at New York 1889. No one
could fault Steinitz’s industry. His move to America refreshed him. He had
never felt wholly settled in Great Britain. While Steinitz mostly got on well
with his fellow London chess professionals, this tiny pioneering band faced
constant financial insecurity, in an age dominated by an almost exclusively
amateur ethos that neither highly valued nor cared much to promote
‘professionalism’ in chess. Chess was no easy calling, even for the
world’s best player in the chess world’s greatest capital. Moreover, as a
foreigner and a Jew, Steinitz also had to endure all too frequent
anti-foreigner and anti-Jewish prejudice in some of the bitterest attacks by
one or two of his actual enemies. At any rate, following the loss of his
financially lucrative column in The Field and his inability to replace it with
anything suitably commensurate, Steinitz was to find a warmer welcome for his
talents in the New World, where the main chess clubs clamoured to attract him
on generous terms for often lengthy local engagements. Steinitz’s economic
circumstances, and even his health, seemed to benefit, at least in his first
decade or so in the USA. In an interview with The New York Tribune , in 1886,
the newly crowned, first world champion recorded that while he had “never 
[been able to] think of becoming a [British] citizen”, he had already, early
on, decided to apply for naturalization in the USA. He became a US citizen, in
1888, shortly before the start of his first world title defence against
Chigorin. In these years, Steinitz and one or two other US and European chess
professionals, enjoyed especially generous patronage by the wealthy Havana
Chess Club. Steinitz and Mackenzie were frequent New York visitors. Inspired
by the success of such tours and, since 1886, Steinitz’s star appeal as the
first official world champion, the club’s well-heeled patrons resolved to
promote further world title matches. Mackenzie declined an initial invitation
to challenge Steinitz for his crown. Undaunted, the Havana Club asked Steinitz
to choose a challenger. These were more ‘gentlemanly’ days. Steinitz chose
well. The only top player to boast a plus score (3/4) against Steinitz,
Chigorin earned his challenge on merit. The result was a splendid encounter
that Steinitz colourfully billed in his International Chess Magazine as “a
fight between an old master of a young school and a young master of an old
school [which] the young school won in spite of the age of its master”.
Chigorin, it should be said, didn’t much care for this characterization.
Though Chigorin liked to attack and to champion the ‘old’ Evans Gambit, he
also played in a genuinely ‘modern’ style. No throwback to an outmoded
romantic attacking past, Chigorin openly admired Steinitz’s strategic depth,
masterly planning and manoeuvring skills and focus on tenacious, ever-concrete
calculation. However, while he shared Steinitz’s forward-looking spirit,
Chigorin didn’t quite have his great opponent’s all-round virtuosity and
simply wasn’t good enough to defeat him. Steinitz won an extraordinarily
bloodthirsty match, by 10 wins to 6 losses, with one draw, the high count of
decisive games no doubt due almost entirely to the highly experimental and
often risky way in which both players battled for the full point. This is the
match in which Steinitz eight times ventured his quasi-outrageous defence to
Chigorin’s Evans Gambit: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bc4 Bc5 4 b4 Bxb4 5 c3 Ba5 6
0-0 Qf6!?. Not to be outdone, Chigorin countered six times with an early form
of Chigorin’s Defence: 1 Nf3 d5 2 d4 Bg4, with four games then continuing 3
c4 Nc6. Some of the most chaotic positions ever seen in world championship
combat occurred in this match, leading to not a few errors, rather more of
them committed by Chigorin. Since the mid-1870s, Steinitz had consciously
considered himself to be in the vanguard of what he increasingly referred to
as a new “modern school”. By the late 1870s, and certainly through the
1880s, most top players came to acknowledge Steinitz’s pivotal role in
driving that ‘modern school’ forward. Despite a growing sense that
something new was afoot and the very ubiquity of the term, however, the many
changes being brought about by the ‘modern school’ still lacked clear
definition. That it stood in contrast to older, more open, direct attacking
styles of play, often involving gambits and even greater material sacrifice,
in a bid to topple kings fast, was vaguely understood, but what more was it?
Steinitz’s many writings, up to the mid-1880s, had been more piecemeal than
comprehensive about all this. In the first four issues of his International
Chess Magazine (January-April 1885), however, Steinitz consolidated many of
his most important insights in a four-part essay on ‘Paul Morphy and His
Time’. This significant piece of work makes clear that, in contrast to the
past, the new ‘modern school’ rested primarily on three main foundations:
1. The recent development of vastly improved means of defence and
counterattack, which had rendered the old ‘romantic’ attacking style,
especially highly speculative gambit play, largely outmoded. 2. An
understanding that chess didn’t teeter on an unpredictable tactical
knife-edge, but was much more broadly balanced in a strategically complex way
that called for the application of more subtly judged planning and manoeuvring
skills. 3. An increasing realization that the scope in chess for innovation
and test by concrete analysis was, in effect, near-endless. Steinitz (and
others) increasingly demonstrated in their games that sacrifices that were not
based on some previously achieved strategic advantage might be riddled with
flaws. Steinitz therefore concluded that, in the absence of grave errors, a
resourceful, well-planned defence might expect to repel the “indiscriminate
and chiefly tactical kingside attack”, while simultaneously laying the
ground for a successful counterattack. In the modern game, he noted, “the
assault against the kingside [now] forms the exception” rather than “the
rule”, having been “superseded by strategical manoeuvres, marches and
counter-marches for gaining and accumulating small advantages at any point on
the board” – not excluding material amassed from the acceptance of most of
the old-style gambits! Steinitz insisted that the successful player must first
seek to alter the balance in a game in his or her favour before launching any
all-out attack. He or she should do this by developing sound and flexible
plans, rooted in the widest range of concrete positional factors (material,
time, space and pawn-structural judgements), and transformed into manoeuvres
that continually adjust to changing circumstances as a game flows. Steinitz
considered that successful “calculations and combinations” tend to emerge
from “delicate shades in the application of position judgement”, likening
them to ways in which “melody [melts] into the harmony and dramatic
expression of Richard Wagner’s [new revolutionary] music”. More than that,
however, Steinitz also believed that to be truly successful, the modern player
must never fear new paths, always ready to take calculated risks and to
innovate. By innovation, he meant primarily a search for new, often bold
systems of play, rather than one-off variations. He trusted that the game’s
breadth, depth and complexity not only provided ample opportunity in which
such experiment might flourish, but that it also generally favoured the
innovator. Steinitz was aware of the value of surprise in chess. In response
to critics of some of his riskier systems, he liked to point out that to
establish the true value of most playable ideas often required many hundreds
of hours of practical test and analysis. All of this has since become an
accepted and enduringly modern chess credo. In 1889, Chigorin, who shared much
of this new understanding, couldn’t yet match Steinitz’s exceptional
profundity, energy, passion and positional skills-set. While Chigorin
contributed gamely to a memorable first title challenge, he remained no more
than a worthy challenger. In 1890-91, however, the Russian champion moved up a
gear, winning both games in a cable match against Steinitz, in two
challengeable lines of the Evans Gambit and Two Knights Defence that Steinitz
had recommended in his Modern Chess Instructor . Chigorin still had an eye on
the possibility of a successful return match. Chigorin was indeed to remain
Steinitz’s main challenger over the next few years and he fared much better
in their second title match, at Havana 1891-92, throughout most of which he
retained a narrow lead. No longer quite at his absolute best, Steinitz only
managed to snatch victory in that match at a very late stage, by 10 wins to 8 
(with 5 draws), scoring three wins and one draw in the last four games. Aged
55, Steinitz suffered increasing physical problems. He had a powerful upper
body, but infirm lower limbs, complained of arthritis and needed a cane to
walk steadily. Between the two Chigorin matches, Steinitz also defended his
title, against a challenge by Gunsberg, at New York 1890-91. Played for lower
stakes and limited to 20 games, this match failed to catch the public’s
imagination as much as the Chigorin contests. Hard to beat, Gunsberg was
renowned more for his assured technique than creative enterprise. He had tied
a lively match with Chigorin, at Havana 1890, and deserved his challenge, but
he didn’t have Chigorin’s combinational flair or star quality. Playing
well within himself, Steinitz won this second title defence, 10.5- 8.5, at a
relative canter.}  *

