{Game 23 W.Steinitz-M.Chigorin World Championship (Game 14), Havana 1889
Chigorin Defence The6th, 10th and 14th games of the 1889 world championship
match featured the earliest games in lines of Chigorin’s Defence, in which
Black exchanges his light-squared bishop for a white knight on f3 and counters
quickly in the centre with ... e5. Steinitz was sceptical about the value of
placing a black knight on c6, in front of Black’s c-pawn, the opening’s
signature development, as it hinders Black’s prospects of eventually
achieving what even such an original thinker as Steinitz considered to be
Black’s ‘natural’ ... c5 break. Steinitz nevertheless recognized that
“the idea of transforming the close game into an open one”, by following
up, whenever possible, by playing ... e5, was “ingenious”. Sadly for
Chigorin, Steinitz demonstrated an impressive, intuitive understanding of how
to successfully thwart such plans, decisively winning the theoretical battle,
at least in this match.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Bg4 3. c4 Nc6 4. e3 e5 5. Qb3 Bxf3 6.
gxf3 Nge7 7. Nc3 exd4 8. Nxd5 Rb8 9. e4 Ng6 10. Bd2 Bd6 11. f4 O-O 12. O-O-O
Nce7 13. f5 $16 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Nf4 15. Qf3 (15. Rg1) 15... Qh4 (15... Qg5 16.
Qg3 $16 Qh6 17. Rg1 Be5 18. Kb1 Kh8) 16. Rg1 h5 17. Kb1 c5 (17... d3 18. Bxd3
Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Rbe8 20. f3 f6 21. Qf1 $18) (17... g5 18. Qg3 $16 Kh7 19. Qxg5
Qxg5 20. Rxg5 f6 21. Bxf4 fxg5 22. Bxg5 $18) 18. Qg3 $18 Ng6 19. Qxd6 Qxe4+ 20.
Ka1 Qxf5 21. Qg3 Qxd5 22. f4 b5 23. Bg2 Qd6 24. Qg5 f5 25. Bh3 Rb6 26. Bxf5 Rf6
27. Be4 Qd7 28. Qxh5 Nf8 29. Qxc5 Ne6 30. Qh5 Qd6 31. Qh7+ Kf8 32. Rc1 Ra6 33.
f5 Nc5 34. Qh8+ Ke7 35. Rxg7+ 1-0

