{Game 24:   World Championship (Game 16), Havana 1889 Dutch Defence Having
failed, playing Black, to achieve any real success with Chigorin’s Defence 
(+1 -4) and early lines of the Slav Defence (-2), Chigorin switched, perhaps
with no little desperation, to the double-edged Dutch Defence, in the 16th
game. As Steinitz then led 9-6, with only five games remaining, Chigorin was
already close to collapse, so a dramatic change in match tactics was hardly
surprising. Steinitz met his opponent’s new challenge, however, with the
same mix of solidity, enterprise and accuracy that Chigorin had found
difficult to counter throughout the match, especially playing with the black
pieces. Steinitz once again achieved and developed an early opening edge, but
perhaps didn’t quite make the most of his advantage in a complex middlegame.
Chigorin missed at least one good chance to get back into the game, then
succumbed in the centre.} 1. Nf3 {1)DWS1889,S.118} f5 2. d4 e6 3. c4 Nf6 4. e3
Be7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. Bd3 d5 7. Bd2 {Steinitz has in mind a plan of queenside
constraint, based on an early c5, for which the text-move is an important
preliminary.} ({White can also play more fluidly, such as after} 7. Qc2 c6 8.
b3) 7... c6 8. c5 {[#] Steinitz now pronounced this move “quite safe [ ... ]
as White can maintain the chain of pawns in reply to ... b6 without being
liable to have his pawns broken up by ... a5 as he would then answer a3”.
Question: But does this plan to gain queenside space convey any real advantage
for White? Answer: there was much fascination and experiment with such plans,
in the 1880s. See, for example, the discussion in Game 17. As noted there,
space does count. However, White is likely to need more than extra queenside
space to press effectively for an advantage in such positions. White ideally
also needs to obtain additional central and/or kingside play, with a fight on
more than one front. Moreover White, whose queenside space advantage is not
yet great, needs to complete his kingside development and get in the moves b4
and a4 to seriously trouble Black. In the meantime, Black can do much in the
centre and on the kingside to promote counterplay. Chigorin’s careless reply,
however (perhaps a finger-slip?), squanders unnecessary tempi.} Nbd7 9. Ng5 Nb8
10. f3 {[#] Black’s poor 8th move has allowed White to develop play on that
all-important second front and Steinitz already has the broad outline of an
excellent middlegame plan firmly in focus. Question: What is that plan? Answer:
White will relocate his knight on g5, via h3 to f2, castle kingside and hold
firm to his pawn on c5. Well aware that he needs to work on more than one
front, he bases his play on two key positional insights: 1. Black can’t
easily undermine White’s queenside grip and is always likely to suffer from
White’s control of greater queenside space in some way, such as after} Qc7 (
10... b6 11. b4 a5 12. a3 Nh5 13. Nh3 axb4 14. axb4 Ba6 15. O-O Bxd3 16. Rxa8
Bxf1 17. Qxf1 {with a comfortable edge.}) {2. That leaves Black with the plan
he adopts in the game, playing for an ... e5 break in the centre, after which
Steinitz probably already judged that, by exchanging his d-pawn for Black’s
e-pawn on e5, White can expect to retain sufficient control of the central
dark squares (especially d4 and c5), to maintain a central and queenside edge.}
11. Qc2 Nh5 12. Nh3 Bh4+ 13. Nf2 e5 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. O-O Be7 16. Ne2 {[#]
This move is an important link in White’s plan. Black has obtained some
genuinely countervailing freedom of action in the centre, but he has still not
done enough to equalize. Question: Why is that? Answer: With the text-move,
White continues the all-important battle for an edge on more than one front.
White simultaneously defends his cramping pawn on c5 and reinforces his grip
on d4. White’s knight threatens to land on d4, followed by moves, such as
Rae1 and Bc3, completely entrenching White’s dark-square bind and overall
command of the board. Chigorin now plays his one remaining queenside card in
an attempt to avoid this.} b6 17. cxb6 {Given that White’s strategy up until
now has, in large part, been based on the maintenance of this pawn on c5, we
should pause here. White gives up his hold on c5 and allows Black to mobilize
his b-, c- and d-pawns, rather than continue with the ostensibly thematic b4.
Question: What is Steinitz up to and was he right? Answer: My guess is that
Steinitz misjudged the tactics.} axb6 18. Nd4 c5 19. Nb5 Nc6 20. Bc3 Qb8 21.
Rfd1 Ne5 22. Be2 Nf6 23. Nh3 Rd8 24. Bf1 Nf7 25. Nf4 d4 26. Bd2 {[#] 26 ...
dxe3?! This is a very interesting moment. Chigorin attempts to equalize by
avoiding all possible pawn weaknesses, but he loses the continuing central
battle and gradually drifts into serious difficulties over the next few moves.
Chigorin has so far avoided any weakening pawn advance, especially on the
kingside, but perhaps this was the moment to strike out boldly with 26 ... g5.
Question: How would you assess such a move? Answer: It is certainly a
candidate move. It may have pawn structurally weakening downsides, but it also
gains space for Black and offers potentially dynamic upsides, not least
opportunities to develop Black’s still undeveloped queen’s rook and bishop.
} dxe3 27. Bxe3 Rxd1 28. Rxd1 Qe5 29. Re1 Kf8 30. Bd2 Qb8 31. Qb3 Nd8 32. Qe3
Qb7 33. Bc4 Qd7 34. Bc3 Ra4 35. Bb3 Ra8 36. Nd5 Nxd5 37. Bxd5 Ra4 38. Bxg7+
Kxg7 39. Qxe7+ Qxe7 40. Rxe7+ Kf6 41. Rxh7 Rb4 42. Nd6 Be6 43. Bxe6 Kxe6 44.
Rh6+ Ke5 45. b3 b5 46. f4+ Kd4 47. Nxb5+ Rxb5 48. Rd6+ Kc3 49. Rxd8 Ra5 50. Rd5
Kb4 51. Rd2 Kc3 52. Re2 1-0

