{Game 25 I.Gunsberg-W.Steinitz World Championship (Game 10), New York 1891
Italian Game Heavy favourite to defeat Gunsberg, Steinitz nevertheless
couldn’t take his Anglo-Hungarian challenger lightly. A considerable
technician, Gunsberg generally sought to wear down opponents rather than
overwhelm them. Steinitz, however, possessed a peerless ability to spot and
exploit ‘small advantages’ (the term itself virtually patented by Steinitz)
, and outdid even his stolid opponent in technical mastery. While as inventive,
resourceful, energetic and enterprising as ever, Steinitz also simply
outclassed Gunsberg technically. This game highlights that technical
superiority, as well as the significant creative gulf between the players.
Gunsberg might defend tenaciously and force many draws, but Steinitz made much
more of his chances.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. c3 d6 6. Nbd2
Ne7 {White’s 6th move remains a current challenge. In reply, Steinitz adopts
a then known plan to transfer his knight to g6, followed by ... c6, with ...
d5 in mind.} ({Also good is} 6... a6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb3 Ba7 {, as in A.Karpov-V.
Korchnoi, World Championship (Game 8), Meran 1981, which continued} 9. h3 Be6
10. Bc2 d5 11. Re1 dxe4 12. dxe4 Nh5 13. Nf1 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Rad8 15. Be3 {
, with White trying to eke out a tiny pull in a still interesting middlegame/
endgame (the game was eventually drawn).}) 7. Nf1 {[#] Rather than play
Karpov’s simpler (and at least equally promising) 7 0-0, Gunsberg adopts one
of Steinitz’s ‘own’, recently invented 19th century manoeuvres. Question:
What is its purpose? Answer: While Steinitz first introduced White’s idea in
the context of a slightly different Spanish Game, it also has relevance here.
Steinitz felt that there was some value in postponing kingside castling and
first mobilizing White’s queen’s knight, via f1, to e3 or g3. In certain
situations, he also speculated on leaving an opportunity to castle queenside 
(see Game 12).} ({In 1891, Steinitz was no doubt aware that I.Gunsberg-J.
Taubenhaus, Bradford 1888, had instead gone (somewhat unclearly)} 7. Qe2 Ng6 8.
g3 Be6 9. Bb3 Qd7 10. Ng5 Bxb3 11. Nxb3 Bb6 12. h3 c6 13. Bd2 a5 14. O-O-O {
with an eventual win for White.}) 7... c6 8. Qe2 {Steinitz much preferred
either} (8. Ng3) (8. Be3) 8... O-O 9. h3 d5 10. Bb3 Ng6 11. g3 {[#] According
to Steinitz, this was: “necessary, but not auspicious for [White’s]
game”. Question: Why is that? Answer: White’s 11th move is clearly aimed
at preventing Black from landing a knight on f4 at an opportune moment. But
having already played h3 (to prevent a possible ... Bg4), this second pawn
move on the kingside creates clear light-square weaknesses and an immediate
target for Black’s forces on h3. Taken together, White’s 8th, 9th and 11th
moves don’t suggest that Gunsberg was sure how best to respond to
Steinitz’s 7th move. White’s main ongoing problem now is that “having
played [Qe2] and advanced his wing pawns on the kingside [he has] difficulty
getting his king into safety” (Steinitz).} dxe4 12. dxe4 Be6 13. Ng5 Bxb3 14.
axb3 Qd7 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Qxe3 b6 17. Nd2 c5 18. Ngf3 Rad8 19. Nc4 {Steinitz
called this move “wasted”. Although still not completely comfortable,
White should probably have played 19 Kf1, embarking immediately on the plan he
shortly adopts to manoeuvre his king to comparative safety on g2.} Rfe8 20.
Ncd2 Re7 21. Kf1 h5 22. Kg2 h4 23. Kh2 Qb5 24. c4 Qc6 25. Rac1 Red7 26. Rc3 Nh5
27. Rg1 Qf6 28. Nf1 Rd1 29. Qe2 hxg3+ 30. fxg3 Ra1 31. N3d2 Qg5 32. Rf3 Nf6 33.
Rd3 Rxd3 34. Qxd3 Nf8 35. Qe3 Qg6 36. Rg2 Ne6 37. Re2 Nd4 38. Rf2 Ra2 {[#]
Black must now win either White’s pawn on b2 or his e-pawn. Bereft of any
active counter-chances, Gunsberg shortly calls it a day rather than play out a
hopelessly lost endgame.} 39. Nf3 Nxf3+ 40. Qxf3 Qxe4 41. Qxe4 Nxe4 42. Re2 Ng5
43. Kg2 Ne6 0-1

