{Game 26 W.Steinitz-I.Gunsberg World Championship (Game 13), New York 1891
Queen’s Gambit Declined Playing White, Steinitz began the match shakily,
deploying unimpressive innovations in attacking lines of the Queen’s Gambit
and scoring only =2 – 1, in the first, third and fifth matchgames. Steinitz
then switched to more solid Queen’s Gambit lines that required Gunsberg to
demonstrate how well he could play against more measured pressure. Less sure
of himself in such calmer, positional waters, Gunsberg began to commit many
more unforced errors than his opponent, who scored a comfortable +2 =4, in his
remaining six games with White. Black’s weak 10th move in this game,
together with Steinitz’s comments on it and the quality of White’s
subsequent manoeuvres, testify to Steinitz’s marked strategic superiority,
flexibility and fluency, evident in all of his best games in the match against
Gunsberg.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. e3 Bb4+ 4. c3 Be7 5. Be2 {White might have
tried to take advantage of Black’s third move,} ({by playing} 5. Bd3 {
, followed by Nbd2, and an eventual e4, a Colle Opening with an extra tempo
for White. That line, however, hadn’t been invented yet.}) 5... O-O 6. O-O d5
7. c4 b6 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. cxd5 {The players have now transposed back into normal
Queen’s Gambit paths (with an extra move played on both sides). White has
chosen a modest variation, but still has the advantage of the move. Steinitz
considered that his 9th move was “best, though most experts, including
Zukertort, usually played [ ... ] b3, followed by Bb2”, a line that still
crops up today.} ({Black need not fear} 9. b3 {but should aim to counter in
the centre at once against it. Black most frequently replies: 9 ...} Nbd7 (9...
c5 10. Bb2 Nc6) 10. Bb2 c5) 9... exd5 10. Ne5 Nfd7 {[#] While theory as we
know it today was still in its infancy, Steinitz nevertheless rightly
considered that the text-move, while it confronts White’s active knight on
e5, is “hardly advisable”. By this, he certainly meant, at the very least,
that the black knight’s retreat was unduly passive. Question: Can you
elaborate? Answer: White’s knight on e5 is a dangerous piece that should be
challenged, but the most natural way to do this is in the course of continuing
Black’s queenside development. Black can choose from at least two better
alternatives: (as against 9 b3 lines) 10 ... Nbd7, followed by ... c5; or 9 ...
c5, followed by ... Nc6. Black’s king’s knight should remain on f6, where
it is already well developed, covering e4, which it may eventually occupy. The
text-move only invites White to support his knight on e5, by advancing his
f-pawn, as in the game, without fear of any likely repercussions at e4.} ({
An early f4 is much more problematic for White, with Black’s knight still on
f6, as in S.Schaller-A.Kveinys, German League 1999, which continued
unconvincingly for White,} 10... Nbd7 11. f4 a6 12. a4 c5 13. Bd3 cxd4 14. exd4
Ne4 15. Qc2 Ndf6 16. Nd1 Ne8 17. Ne3 N8d6 18. Bd2 f6 {, with Black winning the
respective battles for control of e4/e5, and eventually winning.}) 11. f4 {[#]}
Nxe5 12. fxe5 c6 13. Bd2 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Qa4 Nb8 16. Rac1 f6 17. exf6
Bxf6 18. Ne2 Re8 19. Rf3 Qe7 20. Rcf1 Rc8 21. Bb4 Qe6 22. Nf4 Qe4 23. Nh5 Nd7
24. Qa6 Qe8 25. Rh3 Bg5 26. Kh1 Nf6 27. Nxf6+ gxf6 28. Qb7 Qg6 29. Qd7 Kh8 30.
Be7 Rg8 31. Qxc6 Rac8 32. Qxd5 Rg7 33. Bb4 Qd3 34. Qf3 Rc2 35. Bc3 Re2 36. e4
Qxe4 37. d5 Qg6 38. Rg3 Rf7 39. d6 h6 40. h4 1-0

