{Game 27 W.Steinitz-M.Chigorin World Championship (Game 6), Havana 1891/92 Two
Knights Defence In his Moderne Schachpartie (1912), Tarrasch wrote that while
Steinitz took some “insane” risks in his world championship games with
Chigorin, mostly with Black against the Evans Gambit, he could nevertheless
defeat his opponent ‘almost at will’, especially with White. Playing White,
Steinitz tended to play more “rationally” and with “deadly exactitude”.
Steinitz did, however, have one big weak spot with White. Championing a highly
provocative line against Chigorin’s Two Knights Defence, which he couldn’t
quite make work, he scored only +1 -4, in one game of the players’ 1890-91
cable match and four in their 1891-92 world championship encounter. In fact,
this line is less insane than simply double-edged (and very difficult to play
for both sides). Inspired by Steinitz’s sole convincing treatment, in this
game, Bobby Fischer rehabilitated the variation, in the 1960s.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 {This is the critical move, after which Black usually
gambits a pawn. The players now hurtle down the main line. For a pawn, Black
gains a lead in development, a little more space and an early central and
kingside initiative. White can also play 4 d3, heading for quieter lines of
the Italian Game, in an attempt to spoil Black’s fun.} d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+
c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 h6 9. Nh3 {[#] At first sight, this move looks odd. Why
invite Black to ruin White’s kingside pawns, not least because the
alternative, 9 Nf3 e4 10 Ne5, and if 10 ... Bd6 11 d4 exd3 12 Nxd3, which
allows White to hold on to his extra pawn and complete his development more
conventionally, has long been considered quite testing? Question: What is
Steinitz up to? Answer: This is a difficult question! To simplify, I shall
stick largely with Fischer’s rationale, which owes a debt to Steinitz, who
wrote insightfully and at great length on all of the world championship and
cable match games he played against Chigorin in his International Chess
Magazine . The main Fischer/Steinitz judgements are: 1. After 9 ... Bxh3,
White will obtain the bishop-pair on a fairly open board that is likely to
offer bishops considerable prospects. 2. White’s kingside pawns are not, in
fact, as weak as they might at first appear, and even if Black should win
White’s most obviously vulnerable pawn on h3, this only restores material
equality and costs time that White can expect to put to good use by completing
his development and creating play in the centre. 3. Black, too, has strategic
concerns, primarily the weakness of his own split a- and c-pawns (the latter
glaringly beckoning attack by White’s light-squared bishop), and his
somewhat sidelined knight on a5. 4. White’s as yet unmoved phalanx of a-, b-,
c- and d-pawns bristles with energy to expand and if White can meet his
immediate kingside development challenges, his prospects in the centre and on
the queenside may, indeed, outweigh Black’s chances of developing any
telling kingside pressure. W.Lombardy-J.Rubinetti, Nice Olympiad 1974, which
went 9 ... Bxh3 10 gxh3 Bd6 11 Nc3 0-0 12 d3 Nb7 13 Bf3 Qd7 14 Bg2, with the
very slightest of edges for White (though the game was drawn), illustrates how
Fischer thought play might proceed. Fischer considered that White’s bishops
offered White long-term prospects of making progress in the centre and on the
queenside.} Bc5 10. O-O O-O 11. d3 Nd5 12. c4 {[#] Fischer seems to have been
impressed not just by Steinitz’s overall play in this game, but especially
by the deep thought that went into this move. White might also have played the
more solid and subsequently more popular, 12 Nc3, but Steinitz’s choice is
much more ambitious – this time probably not overly. Yet the move clearly
leaves White’s d-pawn backward and weakens d4. Question: Why did Steinitz
choose such a move? Answer: Steinitz acknowledged that “this weakens the
d-pawn”, but expected that White’s coming queenside advance “seems to be
worth that handicap”. White now presses to establish a “clear majority of
two pawns” on that flank. Steinitz was under no illusion that this battle
might be long and difficult, due to Black’s long-term grip on d4 and, in the
event of a likely eventual minor piece exchange on h3, to White’s weakened
kingside pawns. In fact, to realize a clear advantage, White requires some
help from Black!} (12. Nc3) 12... Ne7 13. Kh1 Bxh3 14. gxh3 Nf5 15. f4 exf4 16.
Bxf4 Ne3 17. Bxe3 Bxe3 18. Nc3 Rb8 19. Rb1 Qd7 20. b4 Nb7 21. b5 Nd8 22. Bg4
Qd4 23. Rb3 cxb5 24. Nxb5 Qc5 25. Rf5 Qe7 26. Nc3 Rxb3 27. axb3 Bd4 28. Nd5 Qd6
29. b4 g6 30. Rf1 Nc6 31. Qd2 Kg7 32. Bf3 Rd8 33. Bg2 Be5 34. Qe3 {[#]
Following his earlier, missed opportunities, Steinitz praised the tenacity of
his opponent’s defence, but noted that it was easier for White to attack
than it was for Chigorin to defend. Black’s hold on d4 is not easy to
maintain, while at the same time defending against various White probes on the
kingside. Black can’t, of course, grab White’s pawn on h2. Question: Why
not?} Rd7 ({Answer: After} 34... Bxh2 35. b5 {, followed by c5, White “wins
with facility” (Steinitz).}) 35. Re1 f6 36. b5 Nd4 37. Qf2 Qb8 38. Be4 Ne6
39. Rf1 {[#]} Rf7 {Black misses a simple capture on g6. However, he also loses
after the better} (39... Bd4) 40. Bxg6 Kxg6 41. Qf5+ Kg7 42. Qxe6 Qb7 43. d4
Bb8 44. Rg1+ Kf8 45. Qf5 Bd6 46. c5 Be7 47. c6 1-0

