100,67,67,70,64,82,107,121,107,139,132,120,132,36,-73,-68,-87,-100,-101,-93,
-101,-98,-124,-102,-105,-84,-102,-254,-200,-200,-226,-252,-224,-211,-195,-323,
-194,-259,-242,-273,-243,-273,-297,-297,-301,-301,-301,-281,-298,-298,-285,
-548,-354,-380,-387,-386,-413,-399,-1075,-1248,-1434,-1634,-1684,-1834,-1868,
-1906,-1724,-1420,-2075]} {Game 28 M.Chigorin-W.Steinitz World Championship 
(Game 11), Havana 1891/92 Ruy Lopez Playing White, Chigorin almost exclusively
deployed his favourite Evans Gambit in both of his world championship matches
against Steinitz. In the middle of both contests, however, he did throw in a
single Spanish Game, successfully winning in 1889, but losing disastrously in
the 11th game of their 1891-92 match. In that second encounter, Steinitz
adopted 3 ... d6, in accordance with his recent recommendation that this was
“best” in his Modern Chess Instructor . Presumably ready for this,
Chigorin managed to obtain a little extra space and an early initiative.
Steinitz battled to maintain a massive defensive pawn phalanx, on which he
relied to repel White’s forces. Chigorin made significant early progress,
but then went astray, due to a failure to calculate well at a key turning
point.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Nc3 Bd7 5. d4 Nge7 6. Bg5 f6 $6 (6...
h6 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxb5 11. Qh5 dxe5 12. Qxe5+
Kd7 13. Qf5+ Kc6 14. h4 Qd7 15. Qf3 b6 16. c4 Bxc4 17. Rc1 Kb7 {=
Romanischin-Pancenko, Soviet(ch) 1974}) 7. Be3 Ng6 8. Qd2 a6 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bb3
Na5 11. O-O c6 12. dxe5 fxe5 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Rfd1 Nb7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Ng5 Rf8
17. Nxh7 Rh8 18. Qg5 Nf4 19. Qxe7+ Kxe7 20. Ng5 Rh5 21. h4 Rxh4 22. g3 Rg4 23.
Nf3 Rf8 24. Rd2 Nc5 25. Nh2 Rg6 26. Re1 Nh3+ 27. Kg2 Ng5 28. Rde2 Rh6 29. Re3
Rfh8 30. Nf1 Bh3+ 31. Kg1 Bg4 32. Kg2 b4 33. f4 Bh3+ 34. Kf2 Rf6 35. Ne2 Ngxe4+
36. Kg1 Bxf1 37. fxe5 dxe5 38. Rxf1 Rfh6 39. Rf7+ Kd6 40. Rxg7 Rh1+ 41. Kg2 Nd2
42. Rg6+ Kc7 43. g4 R8h2+ 44. Kg3 Nf1+ 45. Kf3 Rh3+ 0-1

