122,122,98,132,119,187,230,229,229,220,344,454,474,525,527,529,530]} {Game 29
W.Steinitz-M.Chigorin World Championship (Game 16), Havana 1891/92 Ruy Lopez
Steinitz was either a win or two behind for much of the 1891-92 world
championship match, largely due to his excessively wayward experimentation and
lack of success (+1 -3), against Chigorin’s Two Knights Defence. He only
managed to turn things round by returning to the solid Spanish Game, with
which he scored two important wins, in the 14th and 16th games, to draw level,
at six wins each (draws not counting). This set the stage for a dramatic
mutual final spurt to be the first player to reach the 10-wins finishing post.
Steinitz’s superiority in the Spanish rested in his greater mastery of the
kinds of position that arose from his various d3 responses. The
structurally-based games that these systems tend to bring about played more to
Steinitz’s subtle positional and manoeuvring skills in semi-closed play than
to his opponent’s combinational instincts in more open games.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 d5 8. Qe2 O-O 9. Bg5
dxe4 10. dxe4 h6 11. Bh4 Qd6 12. O-O Nh5 13. Bg3 Bg4 14. b4 Bb6 15. a4 bxa4 16.
Nbd2 Qf6 17. Bxa4 Ne7 18. Qc4 Be6 19. Bxe5 Bxc4 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. Nxc4 {
Chigorin must surely have misjudged this position. Although White must now
straighten out Black’s queenside pawns and material remains level, White has
excellent winning chances in the resulting endgame.   [#] Question: Why is
this? Answer: Steinitz considered that White could well afford to unite
Black’s split a- and b-pawns, “as he obtains a strong centre attack and
still has the best of the game on the queenside, in consequence of his open
a-file”. The game’s dynamics now clearly favour White, who is shortly able
to force Black to create further exploitable light-square weaknesses (on e6
and f7), by advancing his f-pawn.} Nxe4 22. Nxb6 cxb6 23. Rfe1 f5 24. Ne5 Rfc8
25. c4 {[#] White is very clearly better here. White’s bishop is an
especially powerful piece with patent potential to dominate both the a2-g8 and
h3-c8 diagonals. Question: What is White’s most immediate winning threat?
Answer: White’s pieces are all now threateningly placed. Black must, however,
immediately attend to the threat of Nd7 (attacking b6), followed by f3,
exploiting the vulnerability of Black’s knights on the open e-file and
winning material.} Ra7 26. f3 Nf6 27. Bb3 Kf8 28. b5 a5 29. Red1 Re8 30. c5
bxc5 31. Rd6 Rb8 32. Rad1 Raa8 33. b6 a4 34. Bxa4 Kg8 35. Nc6 Nxc6 36. Bxc6 Ne8
37. b7 Ra7 38. Rd8 1-0

