670,694,704,704,539,612,476,545,571,762,781,781,415,425,427,425,414,424,434]} {
Game 30 W.Steinitz-M.Chigorin World Championship (Game 20), Havana 1891/92
Queen’s Gambit Declined Having fought back to level-pegging after sixteen
games, Steinitz again went one game down, after committing what he called an
“egregious error”, in the 17th matchgame. Though Steinitz hit back
immediately, outplaying his opponent, in the 18th game, Chigorin duly
responded with a peerlesslyplayed Scotch Game, to lead 8-7 in wins, after 19
games. The knock-about continued with another win for Steinitz, in the 20th
game. Following a draw, in which Chigorin came close to a win, Steinitz then
won two successive games, to snatch a narrow victory, 10-8 in wins. In the
deciding 23rd matchgame, however, Chigorin suffered an “appalling
misfortune” (Steinitz), which had allowed his opponent to deliver a snap
mate from a losing position. Had Chigorin won, the resulting 9-9 score, in
wins, would have triggered an unpredictable three-game match extension.} 1. Nf3
d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. c4 Be7 5. Nc3 Nbd7 {This still topical position
nowadays tends to be reached by the move order, 3 c4 e6 4 Nc3 Nbd7 5 e3 Be7.
Steinitz’s novel reply, however, is unusual.} 6. c5 c6 7. b4 O-O 8. Bb2 Qc7
9. Be2 Ne8 10. O-O f5 11. Qc2 Nef6 12. a4 Ne4 13. b5 Rf6 14. a5 Nxc3 15. Bxc3
a6 16. bxa6 bxa6 17. Rfb1 Rf8 18. Rb2 Bb7 19. Rab1 Rfb8 20. Ne1 {[#] Black
plans ... Bc8, followed by simplifying rook exchanges, thereby escaping the
worst. While White clearly enjoys a considerable, ongoing space advantage, he
must still devise a winning plan. Question: Where is White’s knight going
and why? Answer: To achieve good winning chances, White will almost certainly
have to occupy Black’s glaring hole on b6, by playing a rook to b6, offering
an exchange sacrifice. If Black accepts that offer, White can expect to obtain
a powerful, protected passed pawn on b6 and more than adequate compensation in
the form of continuing, crippling control of Black’s central dark squares.
This must all be well-timed, of course. As Black can do little, White sensibly
prepares the ground for this plan. White’s knight heads for d3, from which
square it exerts pressure against c5 (as well as e5).} Bc8 21. Nd3 Rxb2 22.
Rxb2 Bf6 23. Qa4 {[#]} Kf7 24. Qa3 Bd8 25. Bd1 Rb8 26. Rb6 Nxb6 27. cxb6 Qb7
28. Ne5+ Kg8 29. Ba4 Qe7 30. Bb4 Qf6 31. Qc3 h6 32. Bd6 Rxb6 33. axb6 Bxb6 34.
Qxc6 Qd8 35. Bc5 Bc7 36. Ng6 Kh7 37. Be7 Bd7 38. Bxd8 Bxc6 39. Bxc6 Bxd8 40.
Nf8+ Kg8 41. Nxe6 {Tips and Endpoints Despite a certain falling-off in
Steinitz’s form towards the end of this period, the games played in this
section remain those of a great master, still clearly first among eminent
equals. None of these games was especially easy, as you would expect, as each
was played in a top-class world championship match. Having gained a winning
habit against the very best players in the world since the late 1860s, however,
Steinitz was thoroughly battle-hardened and knew how to graft. While his
greatest strengths lay in his mastery of positional play and the thoroughness
with which prepared and understood his many, mainly systemic opening schemes,
he also took games determinedly to opponents and adjusted to changing
positional and tactical circumstances much better than most. Perhaps three
main messages of wider application might be re-emphasised: 1. Try to go into
all games, like Steinitz, with an initial, practical game-plan, as without one,
you are unlikely to get off to much more than a hesitant start and may, in
extreme cases, risk complete disorientation. 2. Seek to develop as steely a
sense of Steinitz’s self-reliance as you possibly can and positively relish
the point in games where you depart from known paths and must largely depend
on your own judgements. 3. Always seek to remain as adaptable, and especially
tactically alert, as Steinitz, as your more specific middlegame plans unfold,
to ensure that you maximize your chances of spotting and deriving advantage at
critical turning points. Like Steinitz, keep initial game-plans practical.
Beware going into games overburdened with masses of complex variations, many
of which may either be misremembered or require considerable cooperation on an
opponent’s part to derive much benefit from. While it is, of course,
important to be aware of the widest range of typical tactical motifs,
including forcing variations, that you can readily assimilate, it is even more
important to understand as much as possible about the main positional contours
of the kinds of middlegames that might result from your opening choices, so
that you can continue to plan successfully. Keep initial game-plans under
constant review – but also as spare as possible! Self-reliance is a valuable
chess playing trait, which Steinitz possessed in abundance. Preparation always
runs out in chess, so it pays if, like Steinitz, you positively relish having
to depend on your own judgements. Such personal resilience, which isn’t
wholly innate, derives mainly from hard work, knowledge and experience. The
better you understand chess, the greater your likely self-confidence. It also
helps to accept the fact that you can’t banish ‘error’ in chess.
Steinitz often confessed that he made at least as many mistakes as most of his
greatest rivals. Embrace this knockabout spirit – achieve thereby a greater
chess playing serenity and likely reduction in error-count. While plans are
essential in chess to help define and achieve desirable goals, they are rarely
ever immutable. Steinitz may have been head and shoulders above his peers in
his ability to plan over the short-, medium- or longer-term, but he planned
warily. He was also quicker than most to adjust or even abandon his plans
completely when it actually mattered. In most positions, there is generally a
wide range of possible plans, none of them sacrosanct. Recognise that most
‘good’ plans tend to rest somewhere in the broad middle of a wide spectrum
of possibilities. Plan flexibly – be on guard constantly for all changes in
detail and critical turning points!} 1-0

