{Chapter Five Gradual Decline (1893-1900) The year 1892 marked the high point
in Steinitz’s over the board fortunes. Undisputed world champion since 1886,
he had since defended his title three times, twice against his most highly
regarded challenger, Mikhail Chigorin, and once against his next best
available opponent, Isidor Gunsberg. Pleading the demands of his medical
practice, the newly established German star, Siegbert Tarrasch (1862-1934),
had declined an invitation by the Havana Chess Club to challenge Steinitz in a
match that might have replaced the Gunsberg challenge. In 1892, Steinitz’s
eventual conqueror, the precociously talented Emanuel Lasker (1868-1941),
conceded publicly that he did not yet consider his achievements sufficient to
justify a title contest. In the last (December 1891) issue of his
International Chess Magazine , Steinitz wrote that after the second Chigorin
title defence, “a match between myself and any other master is now almost
out of the question, at least for some time to come”. Stressing his age,
continuing health problems and his demanding literary undertakings, Steinitz
reminded readers that he had “already announced [ ... ] before [his Gunsberg]
match [his] intention of retiring from public contests”. In his late-fifties,
Steinitz was under no illusion about his ability to sustain his chess playing
dominance for many more years. His words nevertheless held out the possibility
of defending his title at some point. Steinitz’s chess mind still wholly
alert, his relish for the chessboard battle at the very top had not yet
significantly dwindled. Yet there had been some difficult moments in
Steinitz’s recent personal, as well as chess playing past. In his
International Chess Magazine (February 1888), Steinitz had regretfully
announced that his “most cherished hopes [were] dead and buried in the grave
of [his] daughter [Flora] [ ... ] at the age of 21 years from rheumatism of
the heart”. His daughter’s death clearly came as a devastating personal
blow. He also missed Flora’s invaluable assistance as an involved co-worker
on the production of his magazine. In May 1892, only four years later,
Steinitz’s wife, Caroline, also died, aged 45, as an apparent result of
hepatitis. Two such bleak personal catastrophes, coming in a period during
which Steinitz attained his greatest standing in the chess world, must have
taken their toll on his spirit. With the demise of Steinitz’s International
Chess Magazine , after seven continuous years of successful publication, it
also seemed as if an important chess-historical moment had passed.
Steinitz’s wide-ranging and instructive observations on top players’
styles and historical trends in chess, allied to his deeply insightful game
annotations, including in-depth commentary on all of the games played in all
four of Steinitz’s (1886-1892) world championship matches, had set rigorous
new standards that had been universally acclaimed. Steinitz cited over-work,
apologised for a fourmonth delay in meeting his most recent publication dates 
(though this enabled him to include full coverage of his second Chigorin match,
which ended in February 1892, in the final issue), and expressed a fervent
hope that he might restart the magazine in a year or two, but it didn’t
happen. By 1894, the question was more ‘when’ rather than ‘whether’
Steinitz’s reign would end. Following spectacularly successful match and
tournament results in Europe and America, Steinitz’s youngest potential
successor, Emanuel Lasker, was at last sure that he might dethrone the world
champion, who was more than twice his age. Tarrasch, who had (disappointingly)
tied, 9-9 in wins, with four draws, in a tremendous match against Chigorin, at
St. Petersburg 1893, still shied away from a title match, due to his medical
commitments. Unburdened by such off-board concerns, Lasker, who had
temporarily postponed his ambition to take a PhD in maths (he eventually
obtained his doctorate in 1902), took on and defeated Steinitz, at New York,
Philadelphia and Montreal 1894, scoring 10-4 in wins, with 5 draws. Aged 58,
Steinitz had finally lost his world title to a worthy successor. He took his
defeat gracefully, recognising not just that his age and everincreasing
physical infirmities had been telling factors, but that an opponent, whose
time had clearly come, had convincingly outplayed him. From that point on,
Steinitz’s chess went into gradual, but thankfully far from precipitous
decline. He no longer won great tournaments, but still won many prizes.
Steinitz’s last truly great chess achievement came at the stellar,
all-play-all, six-game, mini-match series, at St. Petersburg 1895/96,
contested by the world’s top four available players. Steinitz finished
second on 9.5/18, behind Lasker (11.5), but ahead of Pillsbury (8) and
Chigorin (7). Tarrasch had been invited to make this a five-player event, but
again declined because of the demands of his medical practice. Probably
unwisely, and in the absence of anyone else who dared challenge the new
champion, Steinitz pressed Lasker to agree to a world title rematch. This
eventually took place, at Moscow 1896-97, and proved to be a mismatch. Lasker
won crushingly against the then 60-year-old exchampion, 10-2 in wins, with 5
draws. Given his age and problematic physical condition, Steinitz’s poor
form was no doubt partly affected by his apparent difficulty in coping with a
cold Russian winter, but this was an inescapably one-sided drubbing. At the
end, thoroughly worn out both physically and in spirit, Steinitz suffered a
serious nervous collapse that required a period of enforced hospitalization.
Thankfully he recovered sufficiently robustly to resume his professional life
fairly quickly, without any obvious deterioration in his mental health.
Steinitz’s last years, however, also became increasingly difficult
financially. His income, which had been at a relatively affluent high point,
up to around 1894, when he still rented a sizeable house in a desirable
out-of-New York, suburban location, began to dip, eventually quite alarmingly.
His cherished plan to follow up Part 1 of his Modern Chess Instructor with two
similarly weighty volumes collapsed, though he did manage to publish an
attenuated Part 2, in 1895. By 1899, Steinitz’s declining economic and
physical health had prompted chess friends to organize charitable help for him,
his second wife and their two infant children. Steinitz’s death certificate
records the twin causes of his death, in 1900, as “chronic endocardia 
(mitral stenosis)” and “acute melancholia”. This was a truly sad end,
but not one we need dwell on. Nowadays such an outstanding world champion, as
Steinitz, could certainly expect to gain much greater financial reward. In the
harsher, Victorian world, in which he actually lived, whose dominant élites
were almost wholly unreceptive to the very idea of ‘professionalism’ in
chess, Steinitz’s achievement in surviving as the first recognisably
successful ‘modern’ professional chess player – in the complete absence
of any inherited wealth – is a much more celebratory landmark. Although
Steinitz might at times be irascible, fall in and out with perceived enemies
and no doubt have better managed some of his business arrangements, he faced a
daunting social, as well as purely economic challenge. We should simply be
glad that this extraordinary man stuck at it! Born with no silver spoon in his
mouth, Steinitz often had to put up with a lot. Landsberger, for example,
recounts that, in December 1898, following an apparent swing among members of
the Manhattan Chess Club against supporting engagements for professional
players, Steinitz felt compelled to resign his longstanding and patently
merited honorary membership. More in sorrow than anger, Steinitz mentioned
that he particularly “deplored [ ... ] a speech by a judge at the club’s
annual general meeting” that included [the judge’s] deeply offensive words
that “gentlemen [should be able] to play a game of chess without
prostituting it by playing for money”. Steinitz and the judge both
apparently agreed not to read any personal slight into their underlying views,
but the prejudice against ‘professionals’ continued. Back on the
chessboard, at any rate, Steinitz’s successor, Emanuel Lasker, greatly
admired his illustrious predecessor and certainly understood that he had
dethroned a revolutionary giant. In challenging Steinitz in 1894, Lasker
believed that he might only hope to defeat Steinitz by confronting him with
his own, hard-wrought principles and playing style. Quoted in Lasker and His
Contemporaries , Lasker revealed in 1906 that he especially valued “the fine
conception of ‘balance’ that Steinitz had discovered [and] resolved to
make no attacks until the balance had been disturbed in my favour”. For the
first time in a match, the old champion met a player of at least equivalent
chess-playing skill, who could even more importantly hoist him by his own
petard – though the age gap, too, made a difference.}  *

