-226,-226,-226,-205,-203,-190]} {Game 31 E.Lasker-W.Steinitz World
Championship (Game 17), Montreal 1894 Italian Game Steinitz began his 1894
world title defence with no little élan. After six games, both players had
won two and drawn two games, and there seemed little between them. In the 7th
matchgame, however, having gained a persistent, virtually winning advantage,
Steinitz unaccountably blundered, gifting his opponent the full point.
Steinitz’s form then perceptibly dipped, allowing Lasker to win the next
four games and sprint to a 7-2 lead in wins at the start of the 12th game.
With the winning post set at the first player to score ten wins (with draws
not counting), Steinitz faced a near impossible task to recover. While the
final eight games ran out a creditable 3-3 in wins (with two draws),
Steinitz’s form implosion had inflicted too much self-damage in the middle
of the match.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Bb6 7.
