{Game 33 W.Steinitz-G.Marco Nuremberg 1896 Slav Defence Following his good
showing at St Petersburg 1895-96, Steinitz’s sixth place at Nuremberg,
including losses against all five of the leading players in the event, was
disappointing. According to Bachmann, Steinitz put it down mainly to his poor
physical condition (“gouty-rheumatism”), and decided to take the waters
shortly afterwards, under the supervision of the famous Pastor Sebastian
Kneipp, at Bad Wörishofen. Bachmann suspected that the old champion’s
earlier precision had simply begun to desert him and feared that he stuck to
too many second-rate openings (including 3 ... f6, against the Spanish Game,
twice!). Against Georg Marco (1863-1923), who later edited the Wiener
Schachzeitung (1898-1916), however, Steinitz reined in all excess and returned
to his classical best.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 {Black’s first three
moves invite White’s to gain space in the centre and would have been a red
rag to a bull to Steinitz, although our understanding of what may be going on
in this line has come on light years since the 1890s.} 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Nf6 {
[#] It is perhaps unfair to criticise this move, as this game was one of the
earliest played in this line, but this slightly naive developing move puts
fewer problems White’s way than the much sharper, modern main line,
beginning 5 ... Bb4+.} (5... Bb4+) 6. Nxf6+ Qxf6 7. Nf3 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9.
Qxd2 Nd7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Qe3 c5 12. dxc5 Qf5 13. Bd3 Qxc5 14. Rhe1 Qc7 15.
Ne5 Re8 16. Kb1 Nf8 17. c5 f6 18. Nc4 e5 19. Nd6 Re7 20. f4 Bd7 21. f5 Bc6 22.
Bc4+ Kh8 23. g4 b6 24. g5 fxg5 25. Qxg5 h6 26. Qh5 bxc5 27. Nf7+ Kh7 28. Ng5+
Kh8 29. f6 gxf6 30. Qxh6+ Nh7 31. Nxh7 Rxh7 32. Qxf6+ Rg7 33. Rxe5 1-0

