{[%evp 0,76,22,22,46,-42,-13,-33,6,18,-2,-20,-18,-38,-5,-20,-18,-36,-29,-47,
-48,-29,-33,-54,-84,-64,-64,-64,-66,-81,-65,-131,-40,-67,-33,-75,-63,-63,-28,
-22,-75,-92,-64,-100,-75,-99,-172,-166,-166,-178,-135,-137,-111,-105,-117,-183,
-211,-215,-207,-272,-164,-205,-153,-177,-106,-164,-163,-163,-155,-227,-236,
-328,-319,-319,-328,-475,-551,-1121,-1276]} {Game 34 G.Maroczy-W.Steinitz
Vienna 1898 King’s Gambit By 1898, a completely new generation had emerged
at the top in chess. In the third great Vienna tournament of 1898, Steinitz 
(now 62) nevertheless defied the years, to finish in fourth place, scoring an
excellent 23.5/36. In Lasker’s absence, Tarrasch and Pillsbury both scored
27.5 points, to share first and second places, with Janowski, in third place,
on 25.5 points. Pillsbury then lost against Tarrasch, 1.5-2.5, in a separate
tiebreak match, Lasker, Tarrasch, Pillsbury, Janowski, and others, were all
much younger than Steinitz, many by two or three decades. Taking the punishing,
double-round format at Vienna into account, Steinitz’s result was all the
more impressive as his poor physical condition had become an increasingly
significant handicap. Hungary’s leading player, Geza Maroczy (1870-1951),
had to concede against Steinitz in a bruising, largely tactical battle that
confirmed that the old master could still gamely compete.} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4
3. Bc4 Ne7 {[#] Buoyed by his lifelong belief that Black could safely accept
all the old open opening gambits, Steinitz constantly sought to revive and
test out new ideas against them. This slightly odd-looking move has some real
point. Question: What did Steinitz see in it? Answer: Steinitz believed that
there was no reason to doubt that Black might respond adequately to whichever 
(of the many) lines that White might now throw at him, as long as he continued
to hold fast to his cramping pawn on f4 (often after ... Ng6), while
completing his development and maintaining a weather eye for a counter-punch
in the centre (usually based on ... d5). Steinitz relished this kind of
complex chess, in which, in the absence of much in the way of ‘known’
theory, both players had to rely largely on their own resourcefulness.} 4. Nc3
c6 5. Qe2 Ng6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qf2 {[#] White’s second relatively
unassuming queen move (in only the first eight moves of the game) raises
doubts about White’s early conduct of the game. While Black has developed
his kingside forces soundly and maintains a flexible stance in the centre,
White can’t seem to generate any real activity. Question: Has White done
anything wrong? Answer: While it might seem surprising, Black has already at
least equalized. White is especially hampered by his inability to threaten
Black’s extra pawn on f4. While White can still look forward to establishing
healthy central pawns on d4 and e4, he seems to lack the time and support of
his queenside pieces to do much with them. It seems that White’s king’s
knight is misplaced. It would work better with White’s queen posted on e2 
(rather than f3). With f4 then under immediate attack by White’s queen,
knight and (after d4), White’s queen’s bishop, White’s game is much
better, suggesting that White should earlier have played 6 Qf2, followed by
Nge2.} d6 9. d4 Be6 {[#]} 10. d5 Bg4 11. Nd4 Bh4 12. Qd2 Nd7 13. Be2 Nde5 14.
dxc6 bxc6 15. Qd1 Bd7 16. Nf5 Bf6 17. Qxd6 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Rad8 {[#] Black is
gradually consolidating a significant plus that is less dependent on absolute
tactical precision than on recognising and remaining within strategic
parameters that have now clearly shifted in Black’s favour. While Black’s
winning chances might have been marginally improved if he had played 15 ...
Be6 earlier, and now 18 ... Rfd8, it is never easy to be certain about such
‘fine-tuning’, during actual play. Question: What key strategic elements
may have been grasped by both players? Answer: Black must surely stand better
as long as he can preserve his thoroughly cramping pawn on f4 and his almost
equally important pawn on c6 (which covers d5). If so, Black is likely to be
able to develop his forces much more effectively than White, with the
likelihood that he will eventually achieve a winning breakthrough on the open
d-file. White’s main problem remains what to do with his unmoved queen’s
bishop, which hems in his equally abject queen’s rook. White must always
think twice about playing Bxf4, White’s natural attempt at freedom, as that
bishop’s exchange for Black’s knight on g6 will then leave Black with
considerable compensation in possession of a raking bishop-pair, an
unshakeably powerful grip on the central dark squares and potentially fatal,
dark-square entry points for a black rook on the d-file (especially d2).} 19.
Qa3 Be6 20. Qa4 Rd7 21. Rb1 Rfd8 22. Bxf4 Nxf4 23. Rxf4 g6 24. Ng3 Be7 25. Qa6
Qe3 26. Rff1 Bh4 27. Rbd1 Qh6 28. Kg1 Qe3+ 29. Rf2 Rxd1+ 30. Nxd1 Qc1 31. Qxa7
Rxd1+ 32. Bxd1 Qxd1+ 33. Rf1 Qd6 34. Qe3 Bc4 35. Re1 Ng4 36. e5 Qb4 37. c3 Qxb2
38. Qd4 Bxg3 0-1

