{[%evp 0,67,22,22,16,11,22,22,23,0,-2,-6,4,4,12,4,4,1,8,6,6,-19,17,14,5,-2,22,
28,29,29,76,94,132,65,79,62,63,65,66,85,45,45,43,58,51,32,29,33,58,66,51,59,63,
43,31,35,35,35,29,33,33,39,45,22,15,26,36,10,119,11]} {Game 35 W.Steinitz-C.
Schlechter Vienna 1898 Italian Game The Viennese player, Carl Schlechter 
(1874-1918), gained lasting fame by tying a challenge match against world
champion, Emanuel Lasker, +1 -1 =8, at Vienna and Berlin 1910, a contest that
was generally held to have been played for the world title, but whose terms in
this regard still resist exact clarification. In 1899, Steinitz, who could
spot talent, confided in an interview with The Glasgow Weekly Herald that
Schlechter was one of the game’s “ablest experts [ ... ] likely to improve
very much as he grows older [and one of the] players of today, such as Lasker,
Tarrasch, Pillsbury [ ... ] and others [who] have adopted my principles, and [
... ] improved upon what I began”. At Vienna 1898, Steinitz was nevertheless
still able to instruct his young Austrian pupil in the art of conducting a
great battle.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 ({
Steinitz adopted this old and still interesting idea, four times at Vienna,
scoring +1 =2 -1. In the first and third games of their 1896-97 world
championship match, Lasker had rudely disabused him of an interest in the even
older,} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nxe4 (7... d5 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. O-O {Black’s main
alternative.})) {Perhaps he basked a little too long in former glories. The
moves of that earlier game, W.Steinitz-C.Von Bardeleben, Hastings 1895, often
complete with fulsome annotations, can be sourced in innumerable books and
websites and, even though much of Steinitz’s justly famous achievement lay
in his brilliantly conceived lead-up play to the diagram below, needn’t be
repeated here.} 6... d5 7. Bb5 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 f6 11. Qb3
Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ne7 13. O-O c6 14. Bd3 Bg4 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Ne5 Bf5 17. Bxf5
Rxf5 18. Rae1 Qd6 19. Bc1 Ng6 20. Ba3 Qf6 21. Nxg6 Qxg6 22. Re7 Rf7 23. Re2 Bc7
24. Rfe1 h6 25. g3 Bd6 26. Re8+ Rxe8 27. Rxe8+ Kh7 28. Bxd6 Qxd6 29. Qc2+ g6
30. Qe2 Qf6 31. Kg2 g5 32. Re6 Qf5 33. g4 Qb1 34. f3 a5 35. a4 Rg7 36. Rf6 h5
37. Qe6 Qc2+ 38. Kg3 {Tips and Endpoints The five games that feature in this
brief, final section, all played during the years of Steinitz’s gradual
decline, still clearly reflect and resonate Steinitz’s strength in his prime.
Steinitz the hard-working innovator, all-out fighter, profound judge of
position and creator of marvellous plans, clever tactician and occasional,
calculated risk-taker is evident throughout. Emerging from an age in which
much narrower views of attack and defence were predominant, Steinitz was the
first great player to develop a thoroughly all-round, recognisably
‘modern’ game and to persuade the world that complex positional
considerations matter as much as tactics in chess. It is, however, important
not to get overly-abstract about Steinitz’s ‘theories’, which neither
attempt to offer any mystical Holy Grail nor set out to elaborate
incontrovertible positional principles that might provide a universal guide to
winning chess. On the contrary, Steinitz’s exhortations are much more
pragmatically down to earth, based on a fairly minimal belief that chess is in
a complex state of balance, which, in games between peers, must first be
disturbed by accumulating sufficient small advantages prior to launching any
realistic, all-out winning attempt. Since Steinitz adumbrated and successfully
incorporated this ‘truth’ into the way he played chess, none of this has
been considered controversial. So, as I end this book, I’d like to suggest
that we all keep Steinitz’s teaching admonitions simple. This book has
already explored at some length much of what Steinitz meant about his theories
and concept of the modern school. Let me now try to sum up what I consider to
be Steinitz’s three over-arching mantras. Throughout all of his writings, as
well as in his games, Steinitz always strove to be: systematic, analytical,
and highly alert to tactics. Steinitz was forever fond of using words, such as
‘systems/systematic’ and ‘analysis/analytical’, by which he generally
indicated that to succeed in chess required a fundamentally investigative/
scientific outlook. He considered that his Modern Chess Instructor was the
first “attempt [ ... ] in any book [ ... ] to base the analysis [of openings]
systematically on general ideas [to] assist [ ... ] judgment [by] the student 
[ ... ] in similar positions”. While he recognised that this was ultimately
a daunting, never-ending task, he felt the need to start it. He consulted all
the main existing international sources on six major openings (in Part 1), and
drew his own conclusions, which he offered to the world either to confirm or
‘falsify’ (the word Karl Popper later evoked to describe the essence of
the scientific process). We all, of course, still do that kind of analysis,
nowadays aided by computers. We still need to grapple with ideas, as well as
variations, and continually work to refine both. Steinitz would have been
amazed at the systematic/analytic power of modern computers, but thoroughly
welcomed them. Just think how strong he might have become if he had been able
to ally his incredibly energetic, innovative, creatively restless, darting and
daring chess mind to modern, 21st century chess engines! If you can continue
to develop and refine such systematic/analytic skills and apply them ever more
effectively to your own game, just think how you, too, might improve – be
inspired by this fundamentally scientific trait in Steinitz! Lasker
consciously recognised and even stood in some awe of Steinitz’s systematic/
analytic insights, work ethic and disciplined approach to chess, practical
success and above all of Steinitz’s incomparable contribution to planning
and manoeuvre that marked a quantum break with the socalled ‘romantic’ age.
He also recognised that Steinitz was simply a born fighter, who, while trying
to order his tactics in a correct positional context, nevertheless revelled in
combinations and considered them central to success in chess} 1-0



[Event "Hastings"]
